          translation: "Yoga is not for one who eats too much or too little, nor for one who sleeps too much or stays awake too long, O Arjuna.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna just dropped the most underrated health advice in human history — 5000 years before any fitness influencer on Instagram. He is basically saying: 'Bro, stop going to extremes.' You know that guy in office who orders double butter chicken with extra naan from Swiggy every lunch, then wonders why he can't focus in the 3 PM meeting? That is 'atyashnatah.' And then there is the other extreme — the colleague who is doing some crazy juice cleanse, eating nothing but air and ambition, posting stories about 'detox journeys' while nearly fainting at their standing desk. That is 'anaashnatah.' Same with sleep. You have got the Netflix bingers — the ones who say 'just one more episode' at 2 AM on a Tuesday and then zombie-walk through Wednesday. And then you have got the hustle-culture bros on LinkedIn posting 'I wake up at 3:47 AM and have already done 14 things before you open your eyes.' Krishna is looking at both these types and saying — neither of you is getting anywhere spiritually. The universe runs on balance, boss. The earth does not spin too fast or too slow. The seasons do not skip steps. Your body is a temple, yes, but it is also a machine — and machines need the right fuel and the right rest. Not too much, not too little. This is the original 'moderation is key' philosophy. Before Ayurveda apps, before calorie counters, before sleep trackers — Krishna laid down the fundamental law: extremes destroy. Balance builds. You want spiritual growth? Start with your plate and your pillow."
