          modernInterpretation: "Krishna is describing the most premium experience available to a human being — and it costs exactly zero rupees. No subscription. No EMI. No coupon code. He says: when you practise yoga consistently — not once-a-month-when-you-feel-spiritual yoga, but daily, disciplined, sincere practice — there comes a point where the mind just... stops. Not dies, not becomes empty, but stops its frantic running. Like a dog that has been chasing its tail finally sits down, panting, and realizes — 'Oh wait, I was chasing myself.' And in that stillness, something incredible happens. You see yourself. The REAL you. Not the 'you' on your Instagram bio. Not the 'you' that your parents describe to relatives. Not the 'you' on your resume. The actual, unfiltered, infinite YOU. And when you see that? Tushyati — you are satisfied. Completely. Fully. Like the kind of satisfaction that a 5-star review from a happy customer cannot give you. The kind that a perfect CIBIL score cannot give you. The kind that 10,000 likes cannot give you. Because all those things satisfy the ego. This satisfies the soul. Most of us spend our entire lives looking for satisfaction in external things — cars, houses, relationships, promotions, biryani. And they give us moments of happiness, sure. But it fades. Always fades. Krishna says there is a place inside you where satisfaction is permanent. Where contentment is not dependent on circumstances. Where you look at yourself and say: 'I am enough.' That is not arrogance. That is awakening. That is the mind finally coming home after years of wandering in the marketplace of desires."
