          translation: "That infinite happiness which is grasped by the intellect and is beyond the reach of the senses — established in that state, one never departs from the truth.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna is talking about a type of happiness that your five senses cannot even detect. Think about that. Every happiness you have ever known has come through your senses — the taste of pani puri, the sight of mountains, the sound of your favourite song, the touch of someone you love. All beautiful. All temporary. All dependent on something outside you. Krishna says: there exists a happiness that is 'atindriyam' — beyond the senses entirely. You cannot taste it, touch it, see it, hear it, or smell it. But you can KNOW it — through buddhi, through the refined intellect. It is like the difference between watching a movie about love and actually being in love. One is sensory, the other is experiential at a level deeper than the senses can reach. And here is the kicker — this happiness is 'atyantikam,' which means absolute, infinite, without end. Not the happiness that peaks when you get your Diwali bonus and fades by January. Not the happiness of a vacation that ends when you see your inbox. This is happiness that does not fluctuate because it is not dependent on anything external. And once you are established in it — 'sthitah' — you do not move from truth. You do not get shaken. Heaviest traffic, worst boss, biggest failure — you remain. Because you have tasted something so real, so deep, so infinite that the temporary pleasures and pains of the world become like ripples on the surface of an ocean. You are no longer living on the surface. You have dived deep. And down there, there is only stillness, only light, only joy."
