          translation: "Having gained that, one considers no other gain to be greater. Established therein, one is not shaken even by the heaviest sorrow.",
          modernInterpretation: "This is Krishna describing the ultimate 'arrived' moment. Not arrived like you bought a BMW. Not arrived like your startup got funded. Arrived like — you have found something so precious, so complete, that if someone offered you the entire world on a golden plate, you would politely say, 'No thanks, I already have something better.' Imagine that. You are at a point where nothing anyone can offer you — no salary hike, no foreign trip, no relationship, no achievement — seems greater than what you already possess within. That is not arrogance or delusion. That is the result of touching something infinite. When you have tasted the ocean, a glass of water does not impress you. And then comes the second part, which is even more powerful: even the heaviest sorrow cannot shake you. Not small sorrows — GURU sorrows. The big ones. Job loss. Betrayal. Death of a loved one. Health crisis. The kind of stuff that breaks people, that sends them spiralling, that makes them question everything. Krishna says: even THOSE cannot move you when you are established in Self-realization. Not because you become heartless or numb — no. But because you have found an anchor so deep that even a tsunami on the surface cannot uproot you. Think of a massive tree. Storm comes — branches shake, leaves fly, but the roots hold. You become that tree. This is not spiritual bypassing. This is spiritual armour. You still feel pain, but pain cannot destroy you. You still face loss, but loss cannot define you. You are shaken but unbroken. That is the promise of yoga."
