          transliteration: "saṅkalpa-prabhavān kāmāṁs tyaktvā sarvān aśeṣataḥ |\nmanasaivendriya-grāmaṁ viniyamya samantataḥ ||24||",
          words: [
            { word: "सङ्कल्प", transliteration: "saṅkalpa", meaning: "imagination/resolve" },
            { word: "प्रभवान्", transliteration: "prabhavān", meaning: "born of" },
            { word: "कामान्", transliteration: "kāmān", meaning: "desires" },
            { word: "त्यक्त्वा", transliteration: "tyaktvā", meaning: "having abandoned" },
            { word: "सर्वान्", transliteration: "sarvān", meaning: "all" },
            { word: "अशेषतः", transliteration: "aśeṣataḥ", meaning: "completely" },
            { word: "मनसा", transliteration: "manasā", meaning: "by the mind" },
            { word: "एव", transliteration: "eva", meaning: "alone" },
            { word: "इन्द्रियग्रामम्", transliteration: "indriya-grāmam", meaning: "the group of senses" },
            { word: "विनियम्य", transliteration: "viniyamya", meaning: "controlling" },
            { word: "समन्ततः", transliteration: "samantataḥ", meaning: "from all sides" }
          ],
          translation: "Abandoning completely all desires born of sankalpa (imagination/mental resolve), and restraining the entire group of senses from all sides by the mind alone.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna identifies the root of all desire in one word: sankalpa — imagination. Every desire you have ever had started not in reality but in your imagination. You were perfectly fine until you IMAGINED having that new iPhone. You were content until you IMAGINED how cool you would look in that car. You were happy single until you IMAGINED a relationship based on some Netflix rom-com. Sankalpa is your mind's movie studio — it creates trailers of futures that do not exist and makes you desperate for them. Your mind is a Zomato of desires — constantly showing you things you did not know you wanted until you saw them. 'You might also like: a bigger house, a thinner body, a cooler friend circle.' And suddenly, you are hungry for things you never needed. Krishna says: step one of serious meditation is to recognize that these desires are not real. They are born of sankalpa — mental projections, fantasies, simulations your brain runs. And the fix? Use the mind to control the senses from ALL sides — samantataḥ. Not just blocking one sense while the others run wild. Not 'I will stop eating junk' while still bingeing content. Not 'I will quit social media' while still gossiping at the chai stall. All sides. Total discipline. And notice — he says 'manasa eva' — by the mind ALONE. Not by running away to the Himalayas. Not by quitting your job. Not by abandoning your family. The battlefield is internal. The weapon is your own awareness. You do not need to change your geography. You need to change your psychology. The mind that creates the desires is the same mind that can dissolve them. That is the beautiful irony of human consciousness."
