          translation: "Supreme bliss comes to the yogi whose mind is peaceful, whose passions are calmed, who is sinless, and who has become one with Brahman.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna is describing the ultimate upgrade of a human being. Not upgrading your phone, your car, or your LinkedIn headline — upgrading your very BEING. He says when three things happen — your mind becomes peaceful (prashanta-manasam), your rajas (passion/restlessness) settles down (shanta-rajasam), and you become free from the stains of past karma (akalmashsam) — then something extraordinary occurs. You become 'brahma-bhutam' — you realize you ARE Brahman. You are not this body. You are not this mind. You are not your job title or your bank balance. You are the infinite consciousness that holds the entire universe together. And when that realization hits? Supreme happiness — 'sukham uttamam' — comes to YOU. You do not chase it. It chases you. Think about that. Your whole life, you have been running after happiness like a dog chasing a car. What happens when the dog catches the car? It does not know what to do with it. But Krishna says: stop running. Settle down. Purify yourself. And happiness — the highest, most supreme form of it — will walk up to your door and say, 'Hey, I have been looking for you.' This is the cosmic joke of existence. The thing you are desperately searching for is desperately searching for you. But it can only find you when you stand still. When your mind is quiet enough to hear its knock. When your passions are calm enough to open the door. When your heart is pure enough to recognize who is standing there. Supreme bliss is not a destination you travel to. It is a homecoming. And the home was always inside you."
