          modernInterpretation: "There is one word in this verse that changes everything: 'sukhena' — easily. EASILY. Krishna says the yogi who is free from sin and constantly practising does not struggle to experience infinite bliss. It comes EASILY. Like breathing. Like blinking. Effortlessly. This is mindblowing because it completely inverts our understanding of spiritual achievement. We think enlightenment is this impossibly hard, monks-on-mountaintops, decades-of-suffering kind of thing. And yes, the journey is tough. The discipline is real. But once you arrive? It is the easiest thing in the world. Like learning to ride a bicycle — the learning is hard, but once you know, you never forget. You just ride. That is what Krishna is saying. 'Brahma-samsparsha' — contact with Brahman. Touch of the Divine. It is not some rare cosmic event that happens once in a thousand lifetimes. For the purified yogi, it is daily life. It is breakfast. It is the morning walk. It is every breath. Constant, easy, infinite bliss. Think of it this way — right now, touching happiness requires so much effort. You need money, plans, people, weather, mood, timing — everything has to align for you to be happy for a few hours. But the yogi who has purified their consciousness? They are like a phone permanently connected to the cosmic Wi-Fi. No buffering. No signal drops. No 'connection lost.' Always connected. Always streaming bliss. And the data plan? Unlimited. No fair usage policy. 'Atyantam sukham' — infinite happiness. Not measured in moments or hours but in infinity. That is the promise Krishna makes. Not to a special chosen one — to ANY yogi who walks this path sincerely."
