          modernInterpretation: "This verse is the nuclear bomb of spiritual wisdom. Krishna is describing a vision so radical, so complete, that if humanity truly understood it, we would solve every problem on Earth in a single day. He says the yogi sees the same Self — the same consciousness, the same divine spark — in EVERY being. In the CEO and the chai-wala. In the Uber driver and the passenger. In the stray dog and the Instagram influencer. In your best friend and your worst enemy. Same Self. Same light. Different lamps. Think about what this means. When you yell at the Swiggy delivery guy for being 10 minutes late — you are yelling at yourself. When you judge the person sitting next to you on the Metro — you are judging yourself. When you are cruel to anyone — you are being cruel to the same consciousness that lives inside your own chest. 'Samadarshana' — equal vision. Not equal in the sense that everyone has the same abilities or deserves the same salary. Equal in the sense that everyone has the same ESSENCE. The same fundamental nature. The same right to dignity, respect, and love. This is the basis of all true morality — not rules, not fear of punishment, not social obligation — but the direct SEEING that you and the other person are literally the same being wearing different costumes. India talks about unity in diversity. This verse IS unity in diversity — at the deepest possible level. Not just 'we are all Indian' or 'we are all human.' We are all ONE. One consciousness playing all the roles in this cosmic drama. When you truly see this — not intellectually, but experientially — hatred becomes impossible. Cruelty becomes absurd. Because hurting another is literally hurting yourself. This is not philosophy. This is physics at the level of consciousness."
