          modernInterpretation: "This is it. This is the verse that makes the Bhagavad Gita the greatest love letter ever written. Not romantic love — something infinitely deeper. Krishna is making a promise here that no human, no institution, no government, no company has ever made or could ever keep: 'I will NEVER leave you. And you will NEVER lose Me.' Let that sink in. Every relationship you have ever had comes with the fear of loss. Your parents will age. Your friends might drift. Your partner might leave. Your children will grow up and move away. Even your own body will eventually abandon you. Everything you love is temporary. But Krishna says: 'See Me in everything — in the sunrise, in the traffic, in your colleague's smile, in the beggar's eyes, in the rain, in the silence — and I promise you, I am NEVER lost to you. And you? You are NEVER lost to Me.' This is the ultimate spiritual security. No more existential loneliness. No more feeling abandoned by the universe. No more crying at 3 AM feeling like nobody cares. The Divine is not sitting in some faraway heaven judging you. The Divine is IN everything, looking back at you through every pair of eyes, speaking to you through every sound, touching you through every breeze. But here is the catch — this is not automatic. Krishna says 'yo mam pashyati' — one who SEES Me. You have to develop the eyes to see. And those eyes do not come from birth. They come from practice. From meditation. From the discipline described in the previous fourteen verses. The yogi who has walked the path of balance, concentration, and self-realization finally arrives here — at the most intimate relationship possible. Not with another person, but with the source of all persons. With existence itself. You and God, inseparable. Forever. That is not religion. That is the deepest romance in the cosmos."
