          modernInterpretation: "This is one of the most liberating verses in the entire Gita. Krishna is basically saying: 'You don't need to quit your job, move to the Himalayas, or delete Instagram to find Me. You can find Me in the auto driver who returns your phone, in the chai wala who knows your order by heart, in the security guard who says good morning even when nobody says it back. If you can see ONE divine thread connecting every living being — from the CEO to the peon, from the stray dog to the peacock — then congratulations, you are living in Me.' This is not about religion. This is about SEEING. Most of us go through life with filters — caste filter, salary filter, looks filter — like a broken matrimonial app. We categorize people before we even meet them. Krishna says: drop the filters. See the same consciousness in the Zomato delivery guy drenched in rain as you see in the temple deity. See the same spark in your irritating colleague as in your best friend. When you stop dividing the world into 'mine' and 'not mine,' 'worthy' and 'unworthy,' something magical happens — you stop being a tourist in this universe and become a resident. You belong everywhere because you see the divine everywhere. And the most beautiful part? 'Sarvathā vartamānaḥ api' — however you are living. You could be stuck in Bangalore traffic, debugging code at 2 AM, or fighting with your landlord over maintenance charges. It doesn't matter. If your inner eye sees unity, you are living in God. No special costume required. No special address. Just special vision."
