          modernInterpretation: "THIS. This is probably the most quoted, most relatable verse in the Bhagavad Gita. Arjuna nails it with four words: Chanchalam (restless), Pramathi (turbulent), Balavat (powerful), Dridham (stubborn). That is not a description of the mind — that is a LinkedIn profile for your brain. Your mind is literally that colleague who won't sit still in meetings, argues with everyone, is annoyingly strong-willed, and refuses to change their opinion even when shown data. And then Arjuna drops the killer analogy: controlling the mind is like controlling the WIND. Not a horse, not a river — the WIND. You cannot grab it. You cannot cage it. You cannot threaten it. It goes where it wants, when it wants, and laughs at your plans. Try this experiment: sit quietly for 60 seconds and think about NOTHING. Your mind will go from 'okay, nothing' to 'wait, what's for lunch' to 'did I reply to that email' to 'I wonder if my ex is happy' to 'why do we park in driveways and drive on parkways' — all in 15 seconds. The mind is the original browser with 47 tabs open, background music playing, and three notifications popping up every second. And Arjuna, the greatest warrior alive, the man who can shoot an arrow through a spinning wheel by looking at a reflection — even HE says 'I cannot control this thing.' If that does not make you feel better about your own scattered brain, nothing will. You are not broken. You are human. Even Arjuna struggled with the same monkey mind you are fighting right now."
