          modernInterpretation: "Krishna does something brilliant here. He does NOT disagree with Arjuna. He does NOT say 'Oh come on, it's easy, just focus!' He says: 'Asaṁśayam' — WITHOUT A DOUBT, yes, the mind is difficult to control. You are absolutely right. BUT — and this is the most important 'but' in spiritual history — it CAN be done. Two tools: Abhyasa (practice) and Vairagya (detachment). Think of Abhyasa like going to the gym. The first day, you can barely lift 5 kg. Your body screams. Your brain says 'Let's go home and order Swiggy.' But you go again. And again. And again. After six months, you are lifting 50 kg and your brain has stopped complaining. The mind works the same way — it is a muscle. Every time you bring it back from distraction, you are doing one rep. And Vairagya? That is the diet plan. You cannot just exercise and then eat junk. Vairagya means slowly reducing your attachment to things that pull your mind away. Not suppressing desires — just loosening their grip. Like going from checking Instagram 200 times a day to maybe 20. Not zero. Just loosening. Krishna is the greatest coach in history because he validates your struggle AND gives you the solution in the same breath. 'Yes, it's hard. No, it's not impossible. Here's the method. Now get to work.' No toxic positivity. No guilt-tripping. Just honest guidance. Every gym trainer, every therapist, every good mentor follows this same template — because Krishna wrote it 5000 years ago."
