          modernInterpretation: "This is it. The SINGLE most beautiful metaphor in the entire Gita. Maybe in all of Indian philosophy. Everything — EVERYTHING — is strung on Krishna like pearls on a thread. Think about a pearl necklace. What do you see? Pearls. Beautiful, round, glowing pearls. But what HOLDS them together? A thread you CANNOT see. Remove the thread and you do not have a necklace — you have pearls rolling on the floor in every direction. Chaos. That thread is Krishna. Now look around you. Your morning chai. The auto-rickshaw outside. Bangalore traffic. Your mother's phone call. Your EMI payment. The sunset. Your heartbeat. The WiFi signal. ALL OF THESE are pearls. Different shapes, different colors, different values. But the thread running through ALL of them — the invisible force that holds this impossibly diverse, chaotic, beautiful universe together — is ONE. And you cannot see it. Just like you cannot see the thread when you look at a necklace. You see India and America and think 'different countries.' You see Hindus and Muslims and think 'different religions.' You see success and failure and think 'different fates.' But the THREAD is the same. The consciousness that powers a king and a beggar is the SAME thread. The life force in a banyan tree and in a mosquito is the SAME thread. This is not philosophy — this is PHYSICS dressed in poetry. Everything is connected, and the connection is invisible, and the connection is DIVINE. Next time you see a pearl necklace — or better, next time you see ANYTHING at all — ask yourself: where is the thread? If you can find that thread in your daily life — in the mundane, in the boring Monday morning meeting, in the Swiggy delivery, in the traffic jam — you have found God. Not in a temple. Not in a book. In EVERYTHING."
