          modernInterpretation: "This is Krishna drawing the most CRUCIAL line in all of human psychology — the line between STRENGTH and AGGRESSION, between DESIRE and OBSESSION. He says: 'I am the strength of the strong — but only the strength that is FREE from selfish desire and blind attachment.' Think about it. There is a difference between the gym bro who works out because he genuinely loves fitness and the gym bro who does it because he is terrified of what his ex will think. Same bicep curl, COMPLETELY different energy. One is Krishna-strength. The other is ego-strength. And then the BOMBSHELL: 'I am desire that does not oppose dharma.' This is NOT anti-desire philosophy. Krishna is not sitting here saying 'suppress everything, become a stone.' He is saying: wanting chai in the morning? DIVINE. Wanting to build something meaningful? DIVINE. Wanting to love and be loved? DIVINE. But wanting your neighbor's car because your ego cannot handle them having a better one? That is desire AGAINST dharma. Wanting that promotion not because you will do good work but because you want to crush your colleague? Against dharma. The desire to order biryani on Swiggy because you are genuinely hungry — perfectly dharmic. The desire to order biryani at 2 AM just because you are doom-scrolling Instagram and saw a food reel — well, that is a GREY AREA, and Krishna is diplomatically silent on late-night cravings. The point is revolutionary: desire itself is not the enemy. MISDIRECTED desire is. Strength itself is not the problem. Strength CONTAMINATED by ego is. This one verse basically destroys both extremes — the people who say 'want nothing' AND the people who say 'want everything.' Krishna says: want the RIGHT things, for the RIGHT reasons. That is where I live."
