          modernInterpretation: "After the four types who NEVER come to God, Krishna now lists the four types who DO — and this is basically the entire spectrum of every person you will find in any temple, gurudwara, church, or dargah in India. First — ĀRTAḤ, the distressed. This is the most HONEST devotee. They come to God because life has punched them in the face and they have nowhere else to go. Job lost. Health crisis. Relationship destroyed. Exam failed. Suddenly the person who never prayed is doing a 108-name chant at 4 AM. Every Indian parent who was 'not really religious' until their kid's board exam results day? Ārtaḥ. We joke about it, but Krishna does NOT mock them. He says they are SUKṚTINAḤ — pious! Because at least they turned TOWARD the Divine instead of toward a bottle or bitterness. Second — JIJÑĀSUḤ, the seeker of knowledge. This person does not come because of crisis but because of CURIOSITY. They genuinely want to know: what IS this reality? Who am I? Why does anything exist? These are your philosophy students, your late-night-Wikipedia-rabbit-hole people, your friends who suddenly got into Vedanta after a random podcast. They want ANSWERS, not just comfort. Third — ARTHĀRTHĪ, the seeker of wealth and material gain. Before you judge — this is ALSO pious! The person who prays before a job interview, who does a puja before starting a business, who goes to Tirupati before their startup funding round. They want STUFF, and they are asking God for it. At least they acknowledge there is a Higher Power who controls outcomes. That is better than thinking your McKinsey presentation skills alone will get you the promotion. Fourth — JÑĀNĪ, the wise one. This person does not want relief, knowledge, or wealth. They want GOD HIMSELF. Not what God can give them — but God. This is the rarest. Most of us spend our entire lives cycling through the first three. And that is OKAY. Krishna calls ALL FOUR of them noble. The journey from ārtaḥ to jñānī is not a straight line — it is a spiral. Sometimes you are all four in the same week."
