          modernInterpretation: "Krishna just revealed something INCREDIBLY intimate here. Out of all four types of devotees, He says the jñānī — the wise one — is the BEST. And then He says something that should make your heart stop: 'I am dear to the jñānī, and the jñānī is dear to ME.' This is not a one-way relationship. This is not employee-boss, not devotee-deity in the transactional sense. This is MUTUAL LOVE. God is saying: 'I love them back.' Think about that. The person who prays for exam results — God helps. The person who prays for money — God helps. The person who prays out of curiosity — God helps. But the person who prays just because they LOVE the Divine, wanting nothing in return? God says: 'THAT one is special to Me.' It is like the difference between people who message you only when they need something versus the one friend who calls just to say 'How are you, da?' — no agenda, no ask, no forwarded WhatsApp good morning image. Just genuine connection. You KNOW which friend is your favorite. Krishna is being HONEST about His favorites, and that is refreshingly human for the Supreme Being. The jñānī is NITYA-YUKTA — always connected. Not connected-when-convenient, not connected-during-festival-season, not connected-only-when-the-WiFi-of-faith-is-strong. ALWAYS. And EKA-BHAKTI — one-pointed devotion. Not bhakti split between God and the stock market ticker. Not devotion divided between the Ultimate Reality and the ultimate Instagram aesthetic. ONE. This is the spiritual equivalent of finding the person who loves you not for your car, your salary, or your six-pack — but just for YOU. And Krishna says: when someone loves Me like that, I love them back just as fiercely. That is the most beautiful promise in the Gita."
