          modernInterpretation: "Krishna first gives the CONSOLATION prize and then drops the NUCLEAR statement. First He says all four types of devotees — the distressed, the curious, the wealth-seeker, and the wise — are ALL noble. All of them. He is not throwing shade at anyone who comes to God with a shopping list. Even the uncle doing a special puja because he wants his son to get into IIT — UDĀRĀḤ, noble. Even the aunty who does a 40-day vrat specifically for a good alliance for her daughter — noble. Anyone who turns toward the Divine, for ANY reason, has done something right. But THEN He says about the jñānī: 'He is My very SELF.' Ātma eva me matam. Not my servant. Not my devotee. Not my follower. MY SELF. Read that again. Krishna is saying: the wise one who has realized the truth is not SEPARATE from Me. He IS Me. This is not promotion. This is not 'Employee of the Month.' This is MERGER. This is the ultimate acquisition — not where a bigger company swallows a smaller one, but where the drop realizes it was ALWAYS the ocean. The difference between the other devotees and the jñānī is simple: the others come to Krishna as SEPARATE beings seeking something from a SEPARATE God. The jñānī comes knowing there is no separation. It is like the difference between someone who uses UPI to send money to someone else and someone who realizes that BOTH accounts are in the same bank, owned by the same entity, and the 'transaction' was just the universe moving money from its left pocket to its right pocket. The jñānī sees ANUTTAMĀM GATIM — the highest goal — which is not heaven, not moksha as some faraway reward, not a better rebirth. The highest goal is the realization that you were never separate from the goal in the first place. You were HOME all along, just dreaming you were lost."
