          translation: "Those whose knowledge has been carried away by various desires surrender to other deities, following various rules and rituals, driven by their own nature.",
          modernInterpretation: "After the COSMIC heights of 'Vasudeva is everything,' Krishna now zooms back to ground level to describe what MOST people actually do — and it is painfully relatable. When desires HIJACK your intelligence, you do not seek the Ultimate. You seek whatever deity, system, or hack promises to fulfill THAT SPECIFIC desire. And you follow whatever ritual or rule that system demands, not because you have thought deeply about it, but because YOUR NATURE drives you to it. This is the spiritual equivalent of going to ten different doctors not because you want the TRUTH about your health, but because you want someone who will tell you what you WANT to hear. You do not want diagnosis — you want VALIDATION for the treatment you have already chosen. Look at how this plays out in modern life. The person whose primary desire is money? They will find a prosperity-gospel guru who says 'God WANTS you to be rich!' and follow every ritual prescribed. The person whose primary desire is control? They will find a system of rigid rules and dogma that makes them feel powerful. The person whose primary desire is comfort? They will find a spiritual path that asks NOTHING of them and promises EVERYTHING. Tais taiḥ kāmaiḥ — by THOSE THOSE desires — meaning various, scattered, all-over-the-place desires. This is not one focused longing. This is a shopping cart of wants, and each want pulls you toward a different checkout counter. Krishna is not saying other deities are false or that other paths are invalid — He is diagnosing the PSYCHOLOGY behind spiritual consumerism. When desire drives your seeking, you do not choose a path based on truth — you choose it based on what it PROMISES you. This is why the same person will do a Shani puja on Saturday, visit a dargah on Thursday, check their horoscope on Monday, and consult a tarot reader on Wednesday — not out of beautiful pluralism but out of PANIC-DRIVEN spiritual shopping. PRAKṚTYĀ NIYATĀḤ SVAYĀ — driven by their own nature. This is the deepest cut. You think you are making free spiritual choices, but you are actually being PUPPETED by your conditioning, your fears, your unexamined desires. The person who sees Vasudeva in everything does not need to shop. When you realize the ENTIRE mall is made of the same consciousness, you stop running from store to store looking for the right product."
