          modernInterpretation: "THIS is the verse that explains 99 percent of human suffering in one line. Krishna says: the moment you are born, you come pre-loaded with a bug in your operating system — the ICCHA-DVESHA program. Desire and aversion. 'I want this' and 'I hate that.' And your ENTIRE life is just ping-ponging between these two. I want that job. I hate this job. I want that person to love me. I hate that person who rejected me. I want biryani. I hate karela. I want weekend. I hate Monday. I want validation. I hate criticism. I want six-pack abs. I hate the gym. Back and forth, back and forth, like a ping-pong ball that thinks it is choosing its own direction when actually it is just being HIT by two paddles called desire and aversion. And from this ping-pong comes DVANDVA-MOHA — the delusion of opposites. You start thinking in binaries. Good-bad. Success-failure. My team-your team. IPL final level tribalism over EVERYTHING. You reduce the infinite complexity of life into likes and dislikes, swipe rights and swipe lefts. And Krishna says this is not something that happens to you at age 25 after a bad breakup. This happens at SARGE — at creation, at birth. You come into the world already confused. Already predisposed to divide everything into 'things I want' and 'things I do not want.' It is the original software bug that nobody tells you about. Your parents do not mention it. Schools do not teach it. LinkedIn does not have a course on it. But it is running in the background of every decision you make. Every fight you have. Every regret you carry. The only way out? Recognizing the program. Seeing the ping-pong for what it is. And slowly, painfully, beautifully — learning to put the paddles down."
