          modernInterpretation: "Krishna does not waste a single word. Three definitions, three sentences, DONE. No 45-minute TED Talk. No 'before I answer, let me tell you a story about my childhood.' Straight answers. First: BRAHMAN is AKSHARA — the imperishable. Not a thing, not a being, not a concept — the INDESTRUCTIBLE foundation of everything. Everything else in your life — your job, your bank balance, your Instagram followers, even your body — is KSHARA, perishable. Brahman is what remains when everything else is deleted. Second: ADHYATMA is your SVABHAVA — your own essential nature. Not your personality, not your profession, not what your Kundli says. Your ACTUAL nature as conscious awareness. The 'you' that was there when you were five, is here now, and will be there at the end. Third — and this is the BRILLIANT one: KARMA is not just 'good deeds' or 'bad deeds' the way your neighbourhood aunty uses it. Karma is VISARGA — the creative impulse that brings beings into existence. Every action you take is a seed that CREATES something. Every Swiggy order, every LinkedIn comment, every angry text — it is all karma, all creating your future reality. Krishna is basically saying: you are not just living life. You are AUTHORING it, one action at a time."
