          translation: "He who meditates on the omniscient ancient seer, the ruler of all, subtler than the subtlest, the sustainer of everything, whose form is inconceivable, effulgent like the sun, beyond all darkness —",
          modernInterpretation: "This verse is POETRY at its finest — Krishna paints a portrait of God that would make any artist weep. Look at the descriptions: KAVI — not just 'God' but the original POET, the one who IMAGINED this universe into existence before creating it. PURANA — the most ANCIENT, older than time itself. ANUSHASHITARA — the cosmic RULER, but not like a politician — like the laws of physics that silently govern everything without holding a press conference. ANOR ANIYAMSAM — subtler than the SUBTLEST. Smaller than the smallest atom. Science has found quarks and leptons, but God is STILL smaller. You cannot find Him with a microscope because He is the one LOOKING THROUGH the microscope. SARVASYA DHATARAM — the SUSTAINER of everything. Not just the creator who built it and left — the one who is MAINTAINING it right now, every second, like a cosmic server that never crashes. ACINTYA RUPAM — inconceivable form. Your mind CANNOT picture this. And that is the point. The moment you think you have figured out God, you have only figured out your own imagination. ADITYA VARNAM — luminous like the SUN. Not moonlight, not candlelight — SUNLIGHT. Self-luminous. Needing no external source. TAMASAH PARASTAT — BEYOND darkness. Not fighting darkness, not removing darkness — simply BEYOND it, the way the sun is not anti-darkness but simply light itself."
