          modernInterpretation: "SULABHAH. Easy to attain. The GOD OF THE ENTIRE UNIVERSE just called Himself EASY TO GET. Let that sink in. We think the divine is some impossibly distant, unreachable thing — like getting a confirmed Tatkal ticket during Diwali, or finding parking in South Mumbai, or getting a reply from that crush who left you on 'seen.' But Krishna says: Nah, I am SULABH. Easy. Available. Accessible. Like UPI. But there is a condition, and it is a beautiful one: ANANYA-CHETAH SATATAM. Without any other thought. Constantly. Not 'remember Me on Tuesdays and Saturdays.' Not 'think of Me when things go wrong and forget Me when things go right.' SATATAM. NITYASHAH. Always. Every moment. Think about who you remember constantly without effort right now. Your phone. Your work deadlines. That person you are crushing on. The EMI due date. Your mind is ALREADY capable of constant remembrance — it is just aimed at the wrong targets. Krishna is not asking you to develop a NEW ability. He is asking you to REDIRECT an existing one. You already know how to obsess. Just obsess over the right thing. And the reward? NITYA-YUKTASYA YOGINAH — for the ever-connected yogi. Not the weekend yogi. Not the New-Year-resolution yogi. The one who stays connected like a phone permanently plugged into its charger. For THAT person, Krishna is not just attainable — He is EASY. The distance between you and God is not measured in kilometers or lifetimes. It is measured in attention. Wherever your attention goes, that is where your reality is. Put it on God constantly, and God becomes the easiest thing in your life."
