          modernInterpretation: "Krishna just called this world two things that should make you stop scrolling and THINK. DUHKHALAYAM — an abode of suffering. ASHASHVATAM — temporary. Now before you get offended and say 'But life is beautiful! Sunsets! Puppies! Butter chicken!' — notice what Krishna is NOT saying. He is not saying life has no joy. He is saying the joy is TEMPORARY. That butter chicken will digest. That sunset will end. That puppy will eventually not be a puppy anymore. Even the best things in this world come with an expiry date printed on them. This is not pessimism — this is PRECISION. And the great souls — the MAHATMANAH — having reached Krishna, simply opt out of the cycle. They do not come back. Not because they HATE this world, but because they have found something so infinitely better that coming back would be like choosing to rewatch a mediocre TV series when you have access to unlimited reality. Think about it in startup terms: this world is a beta product. It has bugs — disease, old age, death. It crashes regularly. The UX is inconsistent — sometimes great, sometimes terrible. And the subscription auto-renews without your consent — that is rebirth. But the MAHATMAS have found the final, perfected version. SAMSIDDHIM PARAMAM — the highest perfection. No bugs. No crashes. No forced updates. No auto-renewal. They have reached the finished product. Why would they come back to beta? The question for us is not whether this world is an abode of suffering. Deep down, we already know it is. The question is: are we going to keep renewing our subscription, or are we going to do the work required to reach the version that needs no updates?"
