          translation: "Those who know that the day of Brahma lasts a thousand yugas and the night of Brahma ends after a thousand yugas — they are the knowers of day and night.",
          modernInterpretation: "Okay. HOLD ON TO YOUR CHAI. Krishna is about to MELT YOUR BRAIN with cosmic mathematics. One Yuga cycle — Satya, Treta, Dvapara, and Kali Yuga together — is 4.32 million years. Now multiply that by ONE THOUSAND. That is 4.32 BILLION years. That is ONE DAY of Brahma. Not one lifetime. Not one era. One DAY. One single morning-to-evening for the creator of the universe. And guess what? The NIGHT is equally long. Another 4.32 billion years. So one full day-night cycle of Brahma is 8.64 billion years. For CONTEXT: our entire Earth is roughly 4.5 billion years old. That means planet Earth — everything from the first microorganism to dinosaurs to the Mughal Empire to your last Swiggy order — has not even lasted HALF of one of Brahma's days. The entire human civilization — every empire, every war, every invention, every love story — fits into the last few SECONDS of Brahma's morning. Your entire life? Not even a nanosecond. Your biggest problem at work? Your EMI stress? That fight with your friend? That Instagram post that did not get enough likes? In Brahma's calendar, it does not even register as a rounding error. And Brahma lives for 100 of his years — each year made up of 360 such days. That is 311 TRILLION human years. And even THAT ends. Even Brahma dies and is reborn. Let that sink in. The being whose single DAY is longer than the age of our planet — even HE is temporary. So when Krishna said in the previous verse that all worlds up to Brahmaloka are subject to return — THIS is what He meant. The scale of time in Vedic cosmology makes modern astrophysics look like a children's counting book. And those who TRULY understand this — AHORATRA VIDAH — the knowers of day and night — they stop sweating the small stuff. Because when you realize your entire existence is a blip in a blip in a blip, either you despair or you WAKE UP. You realize that chasing temporary things in a temporary world on a temporary timeline is the definition of insanity. The only sane response is to seek the ONE thing that is NOT temporary — and Krishna just told you what that is."
