          translation: "This same multitude of beings, coming forth again and again, dissolves helplessly at the coming of night, O Partha, and comes forth again at the coming of day.",
          modernInterpretation: "AVASHAH. Helplessly. That one word should HAUNT you. Krishna says the entire multitude of beings — BHUTA GRAMAH — every living creature, every soul, every conscious entity — comes into existence and dissolves HELPLESSLY. Without choice. Without consent. Without even a notification. You did not choose to be born. You did not fill out a form. You did not accept any terms and conditions. You just... appeared. And when the cosmic night comes, you will just... dissolve. AVASHAH. No opt-out button. No 'unsubscribe from existence' link at the bottom. No exit interview. BHUTVA BHUTVA PRALEEYATE — again and again and again. The repetition is deliberate. Krishna is hammering the point: this is not a one-time thing. This is a LOOP. An infinite loop with no break statement. You are born, you live, you die, you dissolve into the unmanifest, the cosmic day starts again, and you come right back out — same soul, different body, no memory of the last time. Like a Mumbai local train running the same route, same stations, same delays — lifetime after lifetime after lifetime. The passengers think each journey is unique. But it is the same track. Now here is the WAKE-UP CALL embedded in this verse: if you do not do something about it, this is your eternity. Not suffering forever in one place — that would almost be easier to deal with. No, your eternity is an ENDLESS CYCLE of temporary existences, each one feeling like it matters, each one ending in dissolution, each one completely forgotten by the next. The only way out of this cosmic loop is what Krishna described in verses 13 and 14 — Om, remembrance, and reaching HIM. Otherwise? Avashah. Helplessly. Forever."
