          modernInterpretation: "Now Krishna pivots to a WARNING — disguised as a compliment. These people KNOW the three Vedas. They perform rituals perfectly. They drink soma (the OG protein shake of the gods). They are PURIFIED of sin. Their spiritual resume is IMPECCABLE. And what do they pray for? Svarga — heaven. Celestial pleasures. Deva-bhogan — divine enjoyment. Think of it this way: you studied at IIT, cracked UPSC, got an IAS posting, and what did you do with it? Asked for a posting in a comfortable city with good malls. You had access to the INFINITE and you asked for a SLIGHTLY BETTER VERSION OF FINITE. They reach Indra-loka — the divine five-star resort. Unlimited celestial food (no Zomato Gold needed), divine entertainment (Netflix with infinite content), beautiful surroundings (Goa times a million). Sounds amazing, right? Krishna is setting them up. Because the next verse is going to pull the rug out from under this celestial vacation. The problem with praying for STUFF — even divine stuff — is that stuff runs out. Always. This is the spiritual equivalent of a credit card with a limit you did not read in the fine print."
