          translation: "I am equal to all beings; no one is hateful or dear to Me. But those who worship Me with devotion are in Me, and I am in them.",
          modernInterpretation: "This is one of the most MISUNDERSTOOD verses in the Gita, and Krishna addresses it with surgical precision. First part: 'I am EQUAL to all beings. No one is hateful to Me. No one is dear to Me.' Wait — God has no favorites? No chosen people? No VIP list? CORRECT. The sun shines equally on a palace and a slum. It does not choose. It does not discriminate. That is God's DEFAULT setting — total, unconditional, absolute equality. But then comes the second part, and THIS is where it gets beautiful: 'But those who worship Me with devotion — they are IN Me, and I am IN them.' This is not favoritism. This is PHYSICS. If you open the curtains, the sun enters your room. If you keep them closed, it does not. The sun did not choose — YOU did. God is always shining equally on everyone. But the DEVOTEE opens the curtains. The devotee says: 'Come in.' And then something magical happens — a MUTUAL DWELLING. 'They are in Me, and I am in them.' This is not a master-servant relationship. This is LOVE. This is two hearts living inside each other. Like a mother and child. Like the ocean and the wave. You cannot separate them. Krishna is not saying 'worship Me and I will FAVOR you.' He is saying 'worship Me and you will REALIZE that we were never separate to begin with.' The connection was always there. Devotion does not CREATE the connection — it REVEALS it."
