          modernInterpretation: "After the revolution of verse 32, this is the logical conclusion. If even those the world considers 'lowest' can reach the Supreme, then obviously the brahmanas and rajarshis — those with every spiritual advantage — can too. But that is not the real punch of this verse. The real punch is in the second line: 'ANITYAM ASUKHAM LOKAM' — this world is TEMPORARY and JOYLESS. Read that again. Not partially joyless. Not sometimes joyless. Krishna calls this entire world 'asukham.' And before you argue — 'But I am happy! I just got a promotion! My Netflix watchlist is sorted!' — ask yourself: how long does that happiness last? That promotion excitement? Three weeks, then new stress. That new phone? Two months, then a newer model comes out. That vacation? Beautiful while it lasted, now you are back in traffic. Every single joy in this world comes with an EXPIRY DATE. This is not pessimism — this is OBSERVATION. Krishna is not saying life is miserable. He is saying worldly happiness is like cotton candy — sweet for a moment, then gone. Nothing here LASTS. Not youth, not health, not wealth, not relationships, not the body itself. So what should you do in this temporary, impermanent, constantly-expiring world? 'BHAJASVA MAM' — WORSHIP ME. Not because I demand it. But because I am the ONLY thing here that is PERMANENT. In a world of expiring subscriptions, Krishna is the lifetime membership. In a world of 'limited time offers,' He is the ETERNAL offer. You have been born in this world — you did not choose it. But you CAN choose what you do with this fleeting, precious time. Choose the PERMANENT over the temporary. Choose the ETERNAL over the expiring."
