          sloka: 9,
          devanagari: "मच्चित्ता मद्गतप्राणा बोधयन्तः परस्परम् ।\nकथयन्तश्च मां नित्यं तुष्यन्ति च रमन्ति च ॥९॥",
          transliteration: "mac-cittā mad-gata-prāṇā bodhayantaḥ parasparam |\nkathayantaś ca māṁ nityaṁ tuṣyanti ca ramanti ca ||9||",
          words: [
            { word: "मच्चित्ताः", transliteration: "mac-cittāḥ", meaning: "minds fixed on Me" },
            { word: "मद्गतप्राणाः", transliteration: "mad-gata-prāṇāḥ", meaning: "lives surrendered to Me" },
            { word: "बोधयन्तः", transliteration: "bodhayantaḥ", meaning: "enlightening" },
            { word: "परस्परम्", transliteration: "parasparam", meaning: "one another" },
            { word: "कथयन्तः", transliteration: "kathayantaḥ", meaning: "speaking of" },
            { word: "माम्", transliteration: "mām", meaning: "Me" },
            { word: "नित्यम्", transliteration: "nityam", meaning: "always" },
            { word: "तुष्यन्ति", transliteration: "tuṣyanti", meaning: "are content" },
            { word: "रमन्ति", transliteration: "ramanti", meaning: "delight" }
          ],
          translation: "With their minds fixed on Me, their lives surrendered to Me, enlightening one another, always speaking of Me, they are content and delighted.",
          modernInterpretation: "This verse is the original description of SATSANG — spiritual community. Krishna describes devotees who are so absorbed in Him that they NATURALLY talk about Him, teach each other, and find joy in that connection. This is not forced Sunday school attendance. This is people who are genuinely OBSESSED — like a WhatsApp group where everyone actually WANTS to be there.\n\nThink about it — when you love cricket, you naturally find other cricket fans and talk for hours about Dhoni's helicopter shot. When you love food, you and your friends share restaurant discoveries without anyone forcing you. Krishna says His devotees do the same — they 'kathayantaḥ' (speak of Me) and 'bodhayantaḥ' (enlighten each other) NATURALLY, because it brings them 'tuṣṭi' (contentment) and 'rati' (delight).\n\nAnd notice — it is not a solo journey. 'Parasparam' — MUTUALLY. They uplift EACH OTHER. No guru sitting on a golden throne while disciples grovel. It is a community of equals, all pointing each other toward the Divine. The best satsang is not a lecture — it is a conversation where everyone leaves wiser than they came."
