          translation: "Of the Vrishnis, I am Vasudeva (Krishna); of the Pandavas, I am Dhananjaya (Arjuna). Of the sages, I am Vyasa; of the poets, I am Ushana (Shukracharya).",
          modernInterpretation: "PAUSE. Read that second line again. 'Of the Pandavas, I am Dhananjaya.' Krishna just told Arjuna — TO HIS FACE — 'Among your brothers, YOU are My manifestation.' Imagine your boss, your guru, the literal Supreme Being of the universe looking you in the eye and saying: 'You. YOU are the one I chose to represent Me in your family.' The sheer WEIGHT of that compliment. Arjuna must have needed a moment. This is not just flattery — this is RECOGNITION. Krishna is saying: your skill with the bow, your years of tapasya, your refusal to take shortcuts — all of that was ME working through you. You were never alone, Arjuna. Every arrow you shot, I guided. Every battle you survived, I protected. You thought you were just a warrior? You are a VIBHUTI of the Divine. Among the Vrishnis — Krishna names HIMSELF. Not arrogance. Just truth. And among sages — VYASA. The man who compiled the Vedas, wrote the Mahabharata (which contains this very Gita), and gave humanity more wisdom than every university library combined. Vyasa is literally the author of the book you are reading. Meta, right? And among poets — Ushana, also known as Shukracharya. The guru of the ASURAS who was so brilliant that even the demons had world-class education. Intelligence is divine regardless of which side you are on."
