          modernInterpretation: "The second metaphor — MOTHS rushing into fire. This is even more terrifying than the rivers. Rivers at least flow naturally. Moths rush COMPULSIVELY — attracted by the very thing that destroys them. They cannot help it. The light PULLS them.\n\nAnd that is the human condition in a single image. We rush toward the things that consume us — power, fame, wealth, pleasure — with 'samṛddha-vegāḥ' — GREAT SPEED. We do not walk toward our destruction. We SPRINT. Like moths on fast forward.\n\nThe fire does not chase the moths. The moths chase the FIRE. Similarly, death does not chase us. We rush TOWARD it — every day, every choice, every heartbeat is one step closer. And like moths, we are often ATTRACTED to the very flames that will end us."
