          modernInterpretation: "The most EMOTIONALLY beautiful verse. Arjuna gives THREE analogies for how Krishna should forgive him: as a FATHER forgives a son's mistakes, as a FRIEND overlooks a friend's rudeness, as a LOVER forgives the beloved's flaws.\n\nFather, friend, beloved — three relationships, three flavors of divine love. The PARENT love that accepts you despite your failures. The FRIENDSHIP love that overlooks your bad days. The ROMANTIC love that forgives everything because love itself is greater than any mistake.\n\nArjuna is saying — 'Whatever relationship you prefer with me, use THAT relationship to forgive me.' This is the genius of Hinduism's approach to God. You can relate to the Divine as parent, child, friend, master, or beloved. Whatever works. Whatever opens your heart. The form does not matter. The LOVE matters."
