          modernInterpretation: "NOW we enter the most BEAUTIFUL section of Chapter 12 — verses 13 through 20 — where Krishna paints a portrait of His IDEAL devotee. And the first brushstrokes are stunning.\n\n'Adveṣṭā sarva-bhūtānām' — no hatred toward ANY being. Not just humans. Not just nice people. ANY being. The mosquito that bites you at 3 AM? No hatred. The colleague who stole your idea in the meeting? No hatred. The ex who ghosted you? No hatred. This does not mean you become a doormat — it means you REFUSE to let hatred poison your inner world. Because hatred does not hurt THEM. It burns YOU.\n\n'Maitraḥ karuṇaḥ' — friendly and compassionate. Not just tolerant. Not just polite. Genuinely FRIENDLY. Actively COMPASSIONATE. There is a WORLD of difference between tolerating someone's existence and actually wanting good things for them. Krishna is asking for the second one.\n\n'Nirmamaḥ nirahaṅkāraḥ' — without possessiveness, without ego. These two are the TWIN DISEASES of human existence. 'This is MY house, MY car, MY spouse, MY idea, MY achievement.' And ego — 'I am better, I know more, I deserve more.' Remove these two, and 90% of human suffering EVAPORATES.\n\n'Sama-duḥkha-sukhaḥ' — equal in pleasure and pain. Not that you do not FEEL them. You feel them fully. But they do not DEFINE you. You experience joy without clinging and pain without breaking.\n\n'Kṣamī' — forgiving. Not because the other person deserves it. But because YOU deserve the peace that comes from releasing resentment. Forgiveness is not a gift to them. It is a gift to YOURSELF.\n\nThis is just the BEGINNING of the portrait. And already it is clear — Krishna's ideal devotee is not someone who sits in a temple all day. It is someone who walks through the WORLD with an open heart, clean hands, and a steady mind."
