          translation: "He who is always content, a yogi, self-controlled, with firm resolve, with mind and intellect offered to Me — that devotee of Mine is dear to Me.",
          modernInterpretation: "And here comes the MAGIC PHRASE that will echo through the rest of this chapter: 'sa me priyaḥ' — HE IS DEAR TO ME. God just told you what makes someone His FAVORITE. Not rituals. Not donations. Not the number of temple visits. QUALITIES. Inner qualities.\n\n'Santuṣṭaḥ satatam' — ALWAYS content. Not content when things go well. ALWAYS. This is the person who is genuinely okay with what they have RIGHT NOW. Not because they lack ambition, but because their happiness does not DEPEND on external conditions. The promotion comes? Great. It does not? Also great. The chai is perfect today? Wonderful. It is terrible? Also fine. This is not indifference — it is FREEDOM from the tyranny of circumstances.\n\n'Dṛḍha-niścayaḥ' — FIRM resolve. Not the person who reads one motivational post and gets pumped for 20 minutes. FIRM. Unwavering. The kind of determination that does not care about Monday motivation or Friday exhaustion. You decided to walk this path? You WALK it. Through storms, through droughts, through everything.\n\n'Mayy arpita-mano-buddhiḥ' — mind AND intellect offered to Me. Not just emotional devotion (mind) but INTELLECTUAL surrender too (buddhi). You feel for God AND you think about God. Your heart is His AND your brain is His. Both hemispheres. Full coverage.\n\nAnd the result? 'Sa me priyaḥ' — that person is DEAR to Me. Not 'I tolerate them.' Not 'I accept them.' DEAR. Priya. The word you use for someone you LOVE. God is saying — this kind of person? I LOVE them. Not because they are perfect. But because they are REAL, content, determined, and fully surrendered. THAT is what makes God's heart sing."
