          translation: "He by whom the world is not agitated and who is not agitated by the world, who is free from elation, envy, fear, and anxiety — he too is dear to Me.",
          modernInterpretation: "This verse describes a RARE human being — someone who has achieved what I call 'MUTUAL NON-DISTURBANCE.' The world is not disturbed by THEM, and they are not disturbed by THE WORLD. Think about how revolutionary that is.\n\nFirst direction: 'yasmān nodvijate lokaḥ' — the world is not agitated by this person. They do not CREATE drama. They do not walk into a room and make everyone tense. They do not send passive-aggressive texts. They do not start arguments at family dinners. They do not leave behind a trail of emotional wreckage. Their PRESENCE is calming, not threatening. People feel SAFE around them.\n\nSecond direction: 'lokān nodvijate ca yaḥ' — this person is not agitated by the world. Someone cuts them off in traffic? Not disturbed. The news is terrifying? Not shaken. Social media is toxic? Not affected. They live IN the world but the world does not live INSIDE them. The world is like water on a lotus leaf — it touches but does not penetrate.\n\nAnd then the FOUR freedoms: free from 'harṣa' (excessive elation — the dangerous high that always crashes), 'amarṣa' (envy/impatience — the poison of comparing), 'bhaya' (fear — the thief of present-moment peace), and 'udvega' (anxiety — the mental loop that never resolves).\n\nImagine a person who does not get MANIC when things go well, does not BURN with jealousy when others succeed, does not FREEZE with fear about the future, and does not SPIRAL with anxiety about things they cannot control. THAT person, Krishna says, is dear to Him. Not because they are emotionally dead — but because they are emotionally FREE. There is a MASSIVE difference between someone who feels nothing and someone who feels everything but is not ENSLAVED by any of it."
