          translation: "He who is free from expectation, pure, skillful, impartial, free from distress, and who has renounced all selfish undertakings — that devotee of Mine is dear to Me.",
          modernInterpretation: "Every word in this verse is a GEM. Let me break them down because each one is a LIFE LESSON.\n\n'Anapekṣaḥ' — without expectation. Not without EFFORT — without EXPECTATION. You work hard but you do not sit there refreshing your email waiting for the 'congratulations' message. You cook a meal but you do not hover over people waiting for compliments. You do good but you do not keep a mental SCORECARD of who owes you what.\n\n'Śuciḥ' — pure. Not just physically clean. Internally pure. Clean intentions. No hidden agendas. When you help someone, you ACTUALLY want to help — not to get a favor later, not to post about it on LinkedIn, not to feel morally superior.\n\n'Dakṣaḥ' — SKILLFUL. Wait — SKILL is a spiritual quality? YES! Krishna does not want incompetent devotees. He wants people who are GOOD at what they do. A devotee who is a doctor should be an EXCELLENT doctor. A devotee who is an artist should be a BRILLIANT artist. Spirituality is not an excuse for mediocrity. In fact, mediocrity is an insult to the Divine talent installed in you.\n\n'Udāsīnaḥ' — impartial, neutral. Not taking sides in every petty conflict. Not getting dragged into every office politics battle. The wise devotee observes without getting sucked in.\n\n'Gata-vyathaḥ' — gone is the distress. Not that problems are gone — the DISTRESS about problems is gone. The situation might be difficult, but the person inside the situation is NOT suffering.\n\n'Sarvārambha-parityāgī' — renouncing all selfish undertakings. Not renouncing action — renouncing SELFISH action. You can build companies, write books, create art — just do not do it from a place of 'what is in it for ME?'\n\nPut all of these together and you get a human being who is effective, clean-hearted, skilled, unbiased, undistressed, and selfless. THAT, Krishna says, is His kind of devotee."
