          translation: "He who is equal toward friend and foe, in honor and dishonor, in cold and heat, in pleasure and pain, and who is free from attachment —",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna is painting in OPPOSITES here, and the portrait is breathtaking. Equal toward ENEMY and FRIEND. Think about how HARD that is. Your best friend who has been with you through everything AND the person who actively tried to sabotage your career — you treat them with the SAME inner equanimity? Not the same outer behavior — you obviously do not invite your enemy to your birthday party. But the same INNER PEACE regarding both. No burning resentment for one, no desperate attachment to the other.\n\nEqual in HONOR and DISHONOR. When you receive an award, you do not let it inflate your ego. When someone publicly humiliates you, you do not let it crush your spirit. Because you know that BOTH are temporary weather systems passing over the unchanging sky of your true self. Today's honor is tomorrow's forgotten headline. Today's dishonor is next week's irrelevant gossip.\n\nEqual in COLD and HEAT, PLEASURE and PAIN. This is BOTH literal and metaphorical. Yes, the advanced yogi can handle physical discomfort without complaint. But more importantly — the emotional cold of loneliness and the heat of anger, the pleasure of success and the pain of failure — ALL treated with the same balanced response.\n\n'Saṅga-vivarjitaḥ' — free from ATTACHMENT. This is the ROOT that makes all the equanimity possible. Why can this person be equal in all circumstances? Because they are not ATTACHED to any particular outcome. When you are attached, every event is either moving you toward your desire (yay!) or away from it (disaster!). When you are FREE, every event is just... an event. Like watching a movie. You enjoy the twists and turns, but you do not try to CLIMB INTO the screen and change the plot."
