          modernInterpretation: "This verse is the FINAL PORTRAIT before the conclusion, and it is a masterpiece of spiritual psychology.\n\n'Tulya-nindā-stutiḥ' — EQUAL in criticism and praise. This is the HARDEST thing for modern humans. We are ADDICTED to praise. One negative comment on social media ruins our day even if 999 were positive. One critical remark from a parent overshadows a lifetime of love. Krishna's ideal devotee has BROKEN this addiction. Someone praises them? 'Thank you.' Someone criticizes them? 'Thank you.' Same response. Because they know their VALUE is not determined by other people's OPINIONS. Your worth was decided by the ONE who created you, not by the internet.\n\n'Maunī' — contemplative, given to silence. Not mute — but someone who does not WASTE words. In an age where everyone is talking, tweeting, posting, commenting, podcasting — the devotee knows the power of SILENCE. Not because they have nothing to say, but because they know that the DEEPEST truths are found in quiet.\n\n'Santuṣṭo yena kenacit' — content with WHATEVER comes. Whatever. Not 'content when life is going according to plan.' Content with ANYTHING. A feast? Content. A single roti? Content. A palace? Content. A park bench? Content. This is not poverty-glorification — it is FREEDOM from the belief that happiness depends on conditions.\n\n'Aniketaḥ' — without a fixed abode. This does not necessarily mean homeless. It means not PSYCHOLOGICALLY anchored to any place, possession, or situation. You can live in a house but not be imprisoned by it. You can own things without things owning YOU.\n\n'Sthira-matiḥ' — steady-minded. In a world of constantly changing opinions, trending takes, and viral outrage, this person has a MIND THAT DOES NOT WAVER. Not rigid — STEADY. Like a deep river that is not disturbed by surface winds.\n\nAnd through all of this — 'bhaktimān' — full of devotion. That is the golden thread that ties every quality together. Without bhakti, these qualities become dry asceticism. WITH bhakti, they become a love song."
