          translation: "Those who, with the eye of knowledge, perceive the distinction between the Field and the Knower of the Field, and the liberation of beings from material nature — they attain the Supreme.",
          modernInterpretation: "And HERE is the grand finale of Chapter 13. The ENTIRE chapter boils down to this: see the DIFFERENCE between the field and the knower of the field with the EYE OF KNOWLEDGE — jnana chakshusha — and you are FREE. You attain the PARAM — the Supreme.\n\nNotice — Krishna says the 'eye of KNOWLEDGE,' not the eye of the body. You cannot see this distinction with your physical eyes. You cannot see it through a microscope or a telescope. You need a different kind of LENS — the lens of wisdom, discrimination, and deep understanding. This is why self-inquiry matters more than self-improvement.\n\nThe whole chapter has been building to this crescendo. Verse by verse, Krishna has explained what the field is, who the knower is, what knowledge consists of, how Prakriti and Purusha interact, how the gunas trap you, and how equal vision liberates you. And now He says — those who GET IT, those who truly UNDERSTAND this distinction and thereby understand how beings can be FREE from Prakriti's grip — they reach the SUPREME goal.\n\nThis is your graduation certificate from Chapter 13. The course was 'Kshetra Kshetrajna Vibhaga Yoga.' The exam question was simple: Can you tell the DANCER from the DANCE? The SCREEN from the MOVIE? The GOLD from the ORNAMENT? If yes — congratulations. You have passed. You are heading to the PARAM. The Supreme. Game over. Or rather — game UNDERSTOOD."
