          translation: "Of these, Sattva, being pure, is illuminating and free from distress. It binds by attachment to happiness and by attachment to knowledge, O sinless one.",
          modernInterpretation: "Now Krishna gives us the DETAILED PROFILE of Sattva guna. It is NIRMALA — pure, clean. It is PRAKASHAKA — illuminating, like switching on the lights in a dark room. And it is ANAMAYA — free from disease and suffering. Sounds AMAZING, right? Who would not want to be sattvic? It is the guna of clarity, peace, wisdom. It is the state you are in when you meditate perfectly, when you read something profound and it just CLICKS, when you feel genuinely at peace with the world.\n\nBUT — and this is the BRILLIANT twist — it STILL binds you. How? Through SUKHA-SANGA — attachment to happiness — and JNANA-SANGA — attachment to knowledge. You become so addicted to the FEELING of peace that you cannot function without it. You become so proud of your WISDOM that you start looking down at others. 'I do yoga, I eat organic, I read Vedanta — I am better than you.' THAT is sattva binding you.\n\nIt is like the person who becomes so obsessed with their meditation practice that they get ANGRY when someone disturbs their meditation. Ironic, right? Or the intellectual who reads 500 books on spirituality but cannot have a normal conversation with their neighbor. Sattva is the SILK rope. It does not cut your wrists like rajas or tamas, but it still keeps you tied. The golden handcuffs of the spiritual world. You are comfortable, sure, but you are still not FREE."
