          translation: "Sometimes Sattva prevails, overpowering Rajas and Tamas, O Bharata. Sometimes Rajas prevails over Sattva and Tamas, and sometimes Tamas prevails over Sattva and Rajas.",
          modernInterpretation: "This verse explains WHY you are a DIFFERENT person at different times of the day. In the morning after meditation, you feel sattvic — clear, peaceful, wise. By afternoon, rajas kicks in — you are ambitious, restless, checking your to-do list. By midnight, tamas dominates — you are binge-eating chips and watching random YouTube videos. SAME person. Three different states. The gunas are constantly COMPETING for dominance inside you.\n\nIt is like a wrestling match with three fighters in the ring simultaneously. Sometimes Sattva pins down the other two and you feel GREAT — you meditate, you read, you feel compassion for everyone. Then Rajas body-slams Sattva and suddenly you are back to chasing money, status, that promotion. Then Tamas sneaks up behind both and puts them in a chokehold — now you cannot get off the couch and your phone battery dies from scrolling.\n\nThis is deeply VALIDATING if you think about it. You are not 'fake' for feeling spiritual in the morning and lazy at night. You are not 'hypocritical' for meditating at 6 AM and losing your temper at 6 PM. The gunas are CONSTANTLY shifting. The key is not to NEVER have rajas or tamas — that is impossible while you are in a material body. The key is to RECOGNIZE which guna is currently driving and to gradually, consciously, increase the time sattva spends in the driver's seat."
