          modernInterpretation: "Arjuna asks the THREE most practical questions possible. And this is why Arjuna is the PERFECT student. He does not just say 'Oh wow, transcend the gunas, cool bro.' He asks: ONE — what are the SIGNS? How do I IDENTIFY such a person if I meet them on the street? TWO — what is their CONDUCT? How do they actually BEHAVE in daily life? THREE — what is the METHOD? HOW does one actually transcend the gunas?\n\nThese are the questions of a PRACTITIONER, not a philosopher. A philosopher would ask, 'What is the ontological nature of guna-transcendence?' Arjuna asks, 'What does it LOOK like, and how do I DO it?' This is the difference between reading about swimming and actually jumping into the pool. Arjuna wants SWIMMING LESSONS, not a TED talk about water.\n\nAnd notice — he asks all three questions in ONE verse. Efficient. Focused. No rambling. Compare this to Chapter 1 Arjuna who went on for an entire chapter about his confusion. This is a man who has been TRANSFORMED by the teaching. He knows exactly what to ask and asks it cleanly. Three questions, three words essentially — LINGAIH (signs), ACHARAH (conduct), KATHAM (how). This is a student who is READY. And Krishna is about to give him one of the most beautiful answers in the entire Gita."
