          translation: "The Supreme Lord said: He who does not hate illumination (sattva), activity (rajas), or delusion (tamas) when they arise, O Pandava, nor longs for them when they cease.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna begins His answer with the most COUNTERINTUITIVE sign. The guna-transcended person does not FIGHT the gunas. When sattva arises — clarity, peace, knowledge — they do not CLING to it. When rajas arises — activity, desire, restlessness — they do not HATE it. When tamas arises — lethargy, confusion, sleep — they do not PANIC about it. And when any of these STOPS, they do not desperately try to get it back.\n\nThis is RADICAL. Most spiritual seekers spend their entire lives trying to INCREASE sattva and DESTROY rajas and tamas. They fight a war against their own gunas. But Krishna says the truly transcended person has NO war. They watch the gunas come and go like weather. Oh, sattva is here today — nice. Oh, tamas is visiting — okay. Oh, rajas showed up — noted. No clinging, no rejecting. Just WITNESSING.\n\nIt is like living in a house with three roommates. Sattva is the neat, organized roommate who keeps the house clean. Rajas is the hyperactive roommate who is always cooking, working, making noise. Tamas is the roommate who sleeps all day and leaves pizza boxes everywhere. The WISE person does not try to kick anyone out. They just observe, smile, and remember — 'I am not any of these roommates. I am the LANDLORD. They come and go. I stay.' That equanimity, that unshakeable NEUTRALITY toward your own inner states — THAT is the sign of transcendence."
