          translation: "He who is equal in honor and dishonor, equal toward friend and foe, who has renounced all selfish undertakings — he is said to have transcended the gunas.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna completes the portrait. MANA-APAMANA — honor and dishonor are the SAME to this person. Award them a Padma Shri or throw tomatoes at them — their inner poise does not shift. MITRA-ARI-PAKSHA — they are equal toward the FACTION of friends and the faction of enemies. They do not have 'sides.' They do not maintain a mental list of allies and opponents. Everyone is just consciousness wearing different costumes.\n\nAnd then the CLINCHER — SARVARAMBHA-PARITYAGI — they have RENOUNCED all selfish undertakings. Not all action — Krishna already established in Chapter 3 that action cannot be avoided. But all SELFISH initiation of action. They do not START things for personal gain anymore. They act only as instruments of the divine, or in response to genuine need. No hidden agendas. No 'what is in it for me.' No networking with an ulterior motive.\n\nAnd then the LABEL — GUNATITA. Beyond the gunas. This is the official TITLE. If you can be equal in honor and dishonor, friend and enemy, and have given up selfish ambitions — you are GUNATITA. Notice how BEHAVIORAL these signs are. Krishna does not say 'the one who can levitate' or 'the one who glows in the dark.' The signs of transcendence are completely PRACTICAL — equanimity, evenness, selflessness. You do not need supernatural powers to be beyond the gunas. You need MATURITY of consciousness. And that is available to ANYONE who sincerely practices."
