          translation: "For I am the abode of Brahman — the immortal, the imperishable, the eternal dharma, and absolute bliss.",
          modernInterpretation: "The FINAL verse. The GRAND FINALE of Chapter 14. And Krishna ends with one of the most POWERFUL declarations in the entire Gita. He says, 'I am the PRATISHTHA — the foundation, the resting place, the ABODE — of Brahman.' Not 'I am part of Brahman.' Not 'I point toward Brahman.' I AM the foundation upon which the ENTIRE Absolute Reality rests. Brahman — the formless, infinite, ultimate reality — has its HOME in Krishna.\n\nAnd He does not stop there. He says He is the foundation of AMRITA (immortality), AVYAYA (the imperishable), SHASHVATA DHARMA (eternal righteousness), and AIKANTIKA SUKHA (absolute, unconditional bliss). Everything that every human being has ever WANTED — to never die, to never lose anything, to always be righteous, to always be happy — all of that rests in HIM.\n\nThis is the ultimate COMING HOME verse. The entire chapter started with the three gunas binding you — sattva with golden chains, rajas with fiery chains, tamas with iron chains. And it ends with Krishna saying, 'Come to ME, and you will find what is beyond ALL chains — immortality, imperishability, eternal dharma, and absolute bliss.' The gunas are the PROBLEM. Bhakti is the METHOD. Krishna is the DESTINATION. And when you arrive at the destination, you realize it was never about escaping the gunas at all — it was about FINDING the one in whom the gunas themselves find their ultimate rest. Chapter 14 complete. The three gunas explained, their prison revealed, and the escape route laid bare. All you need to do now is WALK it."
