      summary: "Chapter 15 is a compact, diamond-like masterpiece of just 20 verses that reveals the ultimate nature of reality through the metaphor of an inverted cosmic tree — the Ashvattha — with roots above and branches below, nourished by the three gunas. Krishna teaches that one must CUT this deeply-rooted tree with the axe of detachment to reach the supreme abode from which there is no return. He reveals the divine fragment (amsha) dwelling in every living being as the eternal soul, describes Himself as the digestive fire in all bodies, and introduces the three Purushas — the perishable (kshara), the imperishable (akshara), and the Supreme (Purushottama) who transcends both. The one who knows this without delusion knows EVERYTHING.",
