          translation: "The Supreme Lord said: They speak of an imperishable Ashvattha (fig) tree with its roots above and branches below, whose leaves are the Vedic hymns. He who knows this tree is a knower of the Vedas.",
          modernInterpretation: "Welcome to Chapter 15, friends — PURUSHOTTAMA YOGA — and Krishna opens with one of the most MIND-BENDING images in all of spiritual literature. An UPSIDE-DOWN TREE. Roots going UP into the sky, branches hanging DOWN into the world. This is not botany — this is the most powerful metaphor for EXISTENCE itself.\n\nThink about it. Every tree you have ever seen has its roots in the earth and grows UPWARD toward light. But this cosmic Ashvattha tree is INVERTED. Its root is in the SUPREME — in Brahman, in the transcendent — and its branches spread downward into the material world. What does that mean? It means everything you see around you — this world, this life, this reality — is actually HANGING from something above. The SOURCE is not below, not in matter, not in atoms. The source is UP THERE, in consciousness, in the divine.\n\nIt is like looking at a tree's REFLECTION in a lake. The reflection shows branches going down, roots going up. And THAT is exactly what this material world is — a REFLECTION of the spiritual reality. You are living inside the reflection and thinking it is the real thing. You are inside the MATRIX and you do not even know it. And what are the leaves of this cosmic tree? The VEDAS themselves — the hymns, the rituals, the religious practices. They make the tree look lush and full, but they are still part of the tree, not beyond it. Knowing ABOUT the tree is not the same as knowing how to get FREE of it. And that distinction — THAT is what makes someone a true Veda-vit, a genuine knower."
