          translation: "The real form of this tree is not perceived here, nor its end, beginning, or foundation. Having cut down this deeply-rooted Ashvattha tree with the strong axe of detachment...",
          modernInterpretation: "THIS verse is the ultimate RED PILL moment of the Gita. Krishna says — you cannot PERCEIVE the true form of this tree while you are INSIDE it. You cannot see its beginning, its end, or its foundation. It is like asking a fish to describe water. You are so IMMERSED in the material world that you cannot even see it for what it is.\n\nNo beginning. No end. No foundation. Does that not sound exactly like your SAMSARA — your cycle of habits, desires, birth, death, rebirth? Can you point to when your attachment to comfort BEGAN? Can you see where your craving for validation ENDS? Can you find the FOUNDATION of your ego? No, you cannot. Because you are INSIDE the tree, living on its branches, eating its fruits, and thinking that IS reality.\n\nBut then Krishna hands you the WEAPON — 'asanga-shastrena dridhena' — the STRONG AXE OF DETACHMENT. Not a gentle suggestion. Not a meditation cushion. An AXE. And not a flimsy axe — a FIRM, STRONG one. Because this tree has DEEP roots. Your attachments are not surface-level weeds you can casually pluck out. They are DEEP, tangled, ancient roots that have been growing for lifetimes. You need SERIOUS detachment. Not 'I will try to be less attached to my phone' — but a FUNDAMENTAL shift in how you relate to the entire material world. Krishna is saying: you cannot TRIM this tree. You have to CUT IT DOWN."
