          translation: "But other than these two is the Supreme Person (Purushottama), declared as the Paramatma (Supreme Self), who, entering the three worlds, sustains them — the imperishable Lord.",
          modernInterpretation: "HERE IT IS. The verse that gives this entire chapter its NAME. Beyond the perishable (kshara) and beyond the imperishable (akshara), there is a THIRD reality — the UTTAMA PURUSHA, the Supreme Person, the Purushottama. And He is COMPLETELY DIFFERENT from both.\n\nThink of it this way. In a movie, you have the CHARACTERS (kshara — they appear and disappear) and the SCREEN (akshara — it remains unchanged). But there is a third reality — the DIRECTOR. The director is not a character IN the movie. The director is not the screen. The director CREATED both the characters and chose the screen. The director ENTERS the movie through every scene, sustains the narrative, but remains beyond it.\n\nThat is the Purushottama — the PARAMATMA, the Supreme Self. He ENTERS the three worlds (physical, subtle, and causal) and SUSTAINS them, but He is not limited by any of them. He is avyaya — imperishable, unchanging. He is Ishvara — the LORD, the sovereign controller.\n\nThis is a massive philosophical statement. Many schools of thought stop at the akshara — the impersonal, unchanging Brahman — and say THAT is the ultimate reality. But Krishna says NO. There is something BEYOND even the unchanging substratum. There is a PERSONAL supreme reality who is the source of both the changing AND the unchanging. He is not just consciousness — He is the Lord OF consciousness. He does not just exist — He SUSTAINS existence itself.\n\nThis is why Purushottama Yoga is considered one of the most theologically DENSE chapters of the Gita. In three verses (16, 17, 18), Krishna has laid out an entire metaphysical framework — perishable matter, imperishable spirit, and the Supreme Person who transcends and sustains BOTH."
