          translation: "They say the world is unreal, without foundation, without God, not produced by mutual causation — what else is it but driven by desire alone?",
          modernInterpretation: "THIS verse is one of the most PHILOSOPHICALLY loaded verses in the entire Gita. Krishna describes the WORLDVIEW of the demonic person, and it is chillingly MODERN. They believe three things: the world is ASATYA (unreal, meaningless, without objective truth), it is APRATISHTHA (without foundation, without moral basis), and it is ANISHVARA (without God, without any higher governing principle).\n\nSound familiar? This is essentially extreme nihilism. 'Nothing matters, there are no rules, there is no higher power, the universe is just random atoms bumping into each other, and the only driving force is DESIRE.' This is the person who says 'morality is just a social construct' not as a philosophical observation but as an EXCUSE to do whatever they want.\n\nKAMA-HAITUKAM — they believe the entire universe exists only because of DESIRE, meaning lust and craving are the ultimate reality. There is no purpose, no design, no dharma — just animals competing for resources. If you truly believe this, then ANYTHING goes. Cheating is fine because there is no real right or wrong. Exploiting others is fine because there is no cosmic justice. Lying is fine because truth itself is an illusion.\n\nThe DANGER of this worldview is not that it asks hard questions — hard questions are healthy. The danger is that it uses those questions as a LICENSE for selfish behavior. There is a difference between an honest philosopher who wrestles with the nature of reality and a clever manipulator who says 'nothing is real' so he can justify stealing from you."
