          translation: "The faith of each person conforms to their nature, O Bharata. A person is made of their faith — whatever their faith is, that indeed they are.",
          modernInterpretation: "THIS verse is one of the most PSYCHOLOGICALLY profound statements in the entire Gita. 'Yo yac-chraddhaḥ sa eva saḥ' — You ARE your faith. Not you HAVE faith. You ARE faith. What you believe in, what you put your trust in, what you commit to DEEPLY — that is not something you possess. That IS you.\n\nThink about this. Two people look at the same world. One sees OPPORTUNITY everywhere — that is their faith. The other sees CONSPIRACY everywhere — that is their faith. One investor looks at a falling market and sees a buying opportunity. Another sees doom. SAME data, completely different responses. Why? Because 'śraddhā-mayaḥ ayaṁ puruṣaḥ' — a person IS their faith.\n\nThis is basically what modern psychology calls CORE BELIEFS. Your deepest assumptions about reality — 'the world is safe' versus 'the world is dangerous,' 'people are basically good' versus 'everyone is selfish' — these are not just opinions. They SHAPE everything. Your career choices, your relationships, your health decisions, your reaction to stress. You are not a person who HOLDS beliefs. You are a WALKING, BREATHING expression of your beliefs. Change your faith, and you literally change who you ARE. That is why Krishna spends an entire chapter on this."
