          transliteration: "abhisandhāya tu phalaṁ dambhārtham api caiva yat |\nijyate bharata-śreṣṭha taṁ yajñaṁ viddhi rājasam ||12||",
          words: [
            { word: "अभिसन्धाय", transliteration: "abhisandhāya", meaning: "having in view" },
            { word: "तु", transliteration: "tu", meaning: "but" },
            { word: "फलम्", transliteration: "phalam", meaning: "the fruit/result" },
            { word: "दम्भार्थम्", transliteration: "dambha-artham", meaning: "for the sake of show" },
            { word: "अपि", transliteration: "api", meaning: "also" },
            { word: "च", transliteration: "ca", meaning: "and" },
            { word: "एव", transliteration: "eva", meaning: "certainly" },
            { word: "यत्", transliteration: "yat", meaning: "which" },
            { word: "इज्यते", transliteration: "ijyate", meaning: "is performed" },
            { word: "भरतश्रेष्ठ", transliteration: "bharata-śreṣṭha", meaning: "O best of Bharatas" },
            { word: "तम्", transliteration: "tam", meaning: "that" },
            { word: "यज्ञम्", transliteration: "yajñam", meaning: "sacrifice" },
            { word: "विद्धि", transliteration: "viddhi", meaning: "know" },
            { word: "राजसम्", transliteration: "rājasam", meaning: "rajasic (in passion)" }
          ],
          translation: "But that sacrifice which is performed with an eye on the result, or merely for show, O best of Bharatas — know that to be rajasic.",
          modernInterpretation: "The rajasic sacrifice has two VERY recognizable traits: PHALA (you are doing it for the result) and DAMBHA (you are doing it for show). Either one or BOTH. And honestly, this describes about 90% of what passes for 'service' and 'sacrifice' in modern life.\n\nThe businessman who donates ten lakhs to a charity — and makes sure there is a HUGE banner with his photo at the event. The person who volunteers at an NGO — but only on days when the photographer is present. The family that does a massive puja not out of devotion but because the neighbors did one last month and they need to one-up them. DAMBHA — performance spirituality.\n\nOr the OTHER flavor: purely transactional sacrifice. 'God, I will do a special puja IF you give me this promotion.' 'I will fast for 11 Mondays IF I get married this year.' 'I will donate to this temple IF my business deal goes through.' This is not devotion — this is a BUSINESS NEGOTIATION with God. You are treating the divine like a vending machine: insert ritual, receive blessing. And look, it is not the WORST thing in the world. Rajasic sacrifice is still sacrifice. You are still DOING something positive externally. But internally, the meter is running. And Krishna says — that meter LIMITS the result you get."
