          translation: "Austerity that is practised with hypocrisy, for the sake of gaining respect, honor, and adoration — that is said to be rajasic, unstable, and impermanent.",
          modernInterpretation: "Rajasic tapas is PERFORMANCE SPIRITUALITY in its purest form. The motivation? SATKARA (wanting respect), MANA (wanting honor), PUJA (wanting worship/adoration), and DAMBHA (hypocrisy and showmanship). And the result? CHALAM (unstable) and ADHRUVAM (temporary).\n\nThis is the person who does a 30-day meditation challenge — but ONLY because they want to post the completion certificate. The person who does yoga in expensive branded clothes at the trendiest studio, not for inner peace but for the AESTHETIC. The influencer who goes on a 'spiritual retreat' in Bali and comes back with 500 photos and zero transformation.\n\nKrishna nails the RESULT of rajasic tapas: it is UNSTABLE and TEMPORARY. Why? Because the motivation is external. When the likes stop coming, the practice stops. When nobody is watching, the discipline evaporates. When the admiration fades, the austerity crumbles. It has no ROOT — it is held up entirely by the scaffolding of social approval.\n\nCompare this to the sattvic practitioner who meditates at 5 AM regardless of whether anyone knows. Whose practice does not change whether they have 10 followers or 10 million. THAT practice is stable because it is ROOTED in something deeper than other people's opinions. Rajasic tapas is like a plant in a pot on a moving truck — it looks alive but it has no ground. One bump and it falls over."
