          devanagari: "अदेशकाले यद्दानमपात्रेभ्यश्च दीयते ।\nअसत्कृतमवज्ञातं तत्तामसमुदाहृतम् ॥२२॥",
          transliteration: "adeśa-kāle yad dānam apātrebhyaś ca dīyate |\nasat-kṛtam avajñātaṁ tat tāmasam udāhṛtam ||22||",
          words: [
            { word: "अदेशकाले", transliteration: "adeśa-kāle", meaning: "at the wrong place and time" },
            { word: "यत्", transliteration: "yat", meaning: "which" },
            { word: "दानम्", transliteration: "dānam", meaning: "charity" },
            { word: "अपात्रेभ्यः", transliteration: "apātrebhyaḥ", meaning: "to unworthy recipients" },
            { word: "च", transliteration: "ca", meaning: "and" },
            { word: "दीयते", transliteration: "dīyate", meaning: "is given" },
            { word: "असत्कृतम्", transliteration: "asat-kṛtam", meaning: "without respect" },
            { word: "अवज्ञातम्", transliteration: "avajñātam", meaning: "with contempt" },
            { word: "तत्", transliteration: "tat", meaning: "that" },
            { word: "तामसम्", transliteration: "tāmasam", meaning: "tamasic" },
            { word: "उदाहृतम्", transliteration: "udāhṛtam", meaning: "is declared" }
          ],
          translation: "That charity which is given at the wrong place and time, to unworthy recipients, without respect or with contempt — that is declared to be tamasic.",
          modernInterpretation: "Tamasic charity is giving that actively DEGRADES the act of giving. Four markers: ADESHA-KALE (wrong place and time), APATREBHYAH (to unworthy recipients — those who will misuse it), ASAT-KRITA (without respect — you throw the money rather than offer it), and AVAJNATA (with contempt — you look DOWN on the person you are giving to).\n\nThe person who throws coins at a beggar with DISGUST on their face. The person who donates old, torn clothes and feels SUPERIOR for doing so. The person who gives money to someone they KNOW will use it for destructive purposes — funding someone's addiction, enabling someone's harmful behavior, supporting a cause that actually HURTS people.\n\nAVAJNATAM — with contempt — is the most damaging aspect. When you give while making the recipient feel SMALL, you have not really given at all. You have TAKEN — you have taken their dignity. The person who says, 'Here, take this, you NEED it more than me' with a condescending tone — that is not charity. That is a power move disguised as generosity.\n\nTrue charity ELEVATES both the giver AND the receiver. Tamasic charity degrades BOTH. The giver becomes more arrogant, and the receiver feels humiliated. It would have been better not to give at all. This is why HOW you give matters as much as WHAT you give. A single rupee given with love is worth more than a crore given with contempt. The Gita is clear — the ENERGY behind the act determines the act's true nature."
