          translation: "With the utterance of 'Tat' and without aiming at any fruit, various acts of sacrifice, austerity, and charity are performed by those who desire liberation.",
          modernInterpretation: "Now comes TAT — 'That.' While Om is the SOUND of the Absolute, Tat is the POINTER toward it. When you say 'Tat' before an action, you are declaring: 'This is not MINE. This belongs to THAT — to the Supreme, to the Infinite, to something far beyond my little personal agenda.'\n\nANABHISANDHAYA PHALAM — without aiming at any fruit. This is the MOKSHA-SEEKERS' approach. People who want liberation do not perform sacrifices for heaven. They do not do austerity for superpowers. They do not give charity for tax benefits. They do EVERYTHING as an offering to TAT — to that nameless, formless, infinite Reality.\n\nIt is like the difference between a river that flows into a DAM (where the water is captured and used for a purpose) versus a river that flows into the OCEAN (where it merges and loses its separate identity). Rajasic action flows into the dam of personal benefit. Sattvic action, marked by 'Tat,' flows into the ocean of the Absolute.\n\nThe word TAT is also beautifully humble. You are not even NAMING God. You are not claiming to know what the Ultimate Reality is. You are just saying 'THAT' — pointing in the direction of something you know exists but cannot fully grasp. It is the spirituality of AWE rather than the spirituality of certainty. And there is something deeply HONEST about that. The greatest seekers are not those who claim to have all the answers. They are the ones who point toward the mystery and say, simply, 'THAT.'"
