          translation: "Steadfastness in sacrifice, austerity, and charity is also called 'Sat.' And action performed for the sake of That (Brahman) is also designated as 'Sat.'",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna deepens the meaning of SAT even further. Not only is SAT used for praiseworthy actions, but STHITI — STEADFASTNESS — in sacrifice, austerity, and charity is ALSO called Sat. And any action performed TAD-ARTHIYAM — for the sake of THAT (Brahman, the Supreme) — is ALSO Sat.\n\nThis is profound. CONSISTENCY in spiritual practice is itself a form of truth. The person who meditates every day for twenty years — that STEADFASTNESS is Sat. Not just the meditation, but the COMMITMENT to it. Not just the charity, but the PERSISTENCE of charitable living. It is one thing to do a good deed. It is another thing entirely to LIVE as a good deed, day after day, year after year.\n\nAnd then the ultimate qualifier: TAD-ARTHIYAM — done for the sake of THAT. When all your actions — your work, your worship, your giving, your discipline — are oriented not toward your ego but toward the SUPREME REALITY, then everything you do becomes Sat. Your morning jog becomes Sat. Your office work becomes Sat. Your cooking becomes Sat. Not because the action itself is special, but because the INTENTION behind it points toward the Infinite.\n\nThis is Krishna collapsing the entire spiritual life into one word. Om is the SOUND of Brahman. Tat is the POINTER to Brahman. Sat is the NATURE of Brahman expressed through your steady, devoted, truthful actions. Three syllables. The entire path of liberation."
