          translation: "Arjuna said: O mighty-armed one, I wish to know the truth about renunciation (sannyasa) and relinquishment (tyaga) separately, O Hrishikesha, O slayer of Keshi.",
          modernInterpretation: "Welcome to Chapter 18 — the GRAND FINALE. MOKSHA SANNYASA YOGA. The Yoga of Liberation through Renunciation. This is the LONGEST chapter of the Gita, 78 verses of pure concentrated wisdom, and Arjuna opens it with a question that has confused spiritual seekers for THOUSANDS of years: What is the difference between SANNYASA and TYAGA?\n\nThink about it — in everyday language, both words seem to mean 'giving up.' But Arjuna senses there is a SUBTLE but CRITICAL difference. It is like asking: What is the difference between QUITTING your job and DELEGATING your work? Both involve stepping back, but the INTENT and the OUTCOME are completely different.\n\nNotice how Arjuna addresses Krishna with THREE names — Mahabaho (mighty-armed), Hrishikesha (master of senses), and Keshi-nishudana (slayer of Keshi). This is not flattery. This is a student who has been TRANSFORMED over 17 chapters, showing DEEP respect before asking the FINAL question. He is basically saying: 'Before we wrap up, I need absolute CLARITY on this one thing — what should I actually GIVE UP, and HOW should I give it up?' And this question will unlock the entire concluding teaching of the Gita."
