          translation: "The Supreme Lord said: The learned understand sannyasa as the giving up of desire-motivated actions. The wise declare tyaga as the abandonment of the fruits of all actions.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna drops the DEFINITIVE answer right away. SANNYASA means giving up DESIRE-DRIVEN actions entirely — like quitting your job because you do not want the stress of chasing promotions. TYAGA means doing ALL your work but giving up your ATTACHMENT to the results — like going to your job, giving it your BEST, but not obsessing over the bonus at the end of the year.\n\nThis is such a PRACTICAL distinction. Think about it in terms of a student studying for exams. Sannyasa would be saying, 'I will not study for marks at all — I reject the entire system.' Tyaga would be saying, 'I WILL study with full effort, but I will not tie my SELF-WORTH to the marks I get.' See the difference? One is about ABANDONING the activity, the other is about abandoning the EMOTIONAL GRIP of the outcome.\n\nAnd Krishna subtly tells you which one He prefers by using the word 'vicakshana' — the truly DISCERNING ones — for those who define tyaga. The wise do not run AWAY from action. They run away from ATTACHMENT to results. This is the Gita's CONSISTENT message from Chapter 2 onwards, and now in the final chapter, Krishna is locking it in permanently."
