          modernInterpretation: "Krishna says 'NISHCHAYAM SHRINU' — hear My DEFINITIVE conclusion. Not opinion, not suggestion — CONCLUSION. He is about to END the debate once and for all. And He calls Arjuna 'Purusha-vyaghra' — TIGER among men. When was the last time someone called you a tiger before giving you life advice? Krishna knows how to MOTIVATE His student.\n\nAnd the framework? THREE TYPES. Of course. Because this is the Gita, and EVERYTHING comes in threes — three gunas (sattva, rajas, tamas), three types of food, three types of faith, three types of knowledge. Now three types of TYAGA. Krishna is essentially saying: 'The question is not WHETHER to renounce. The question is HOW you renounce, and that depends on which GUNA is driving your renunciation.'\n\nThis is like someone asking, 'Should I leave my job?' And a good mentor saying, 'Well, ARE you leaving because you found your true purpose (sattvic), because you are chasing a bigger salary elsewhere (rajasic), or because you are just LAZY and do not want to work (tamasic)?' The ACTION looks the same — resignation letter submitted. But the QUALITY of that decision is completely different based on what is BEHIND it."
