          translation: "The renunciation of prescribed duties is not proper. Abandoning them out of delusion is declared to be tamasic (in the mode of ignorance).",
          modernInterpretation: "Now Krishna starts classifying the THREE types of tyaga, and He begins with the WORST one. TAMASIC renunciation — giving up your DUTY because you are confused, lazy, or deluded. This is the person who says 'I am renouncing worldly life' but what they actually mean is 'I do not want to deal with responsibilities.'\n\nWe ALL know someone like this. The student who drops out not because they have a startup idea, but because they just cannot handle the discipline of studying. The employee who quits not because they found their calling, but because they cannot handle a 9-to-5 schedule. The parent who emotionally checks out not because of spiritual growth, but because parenting is HARD.\n\nKrishna uses the word MOHAT — out of DELUSION. This person has FOOLED themselves into thinking their laziness is enlightenment. They have rebranded their avoidance as 'detachment.' It is like someone who binge-watches Netflix all day and calls it 'living in the present moment.' No, buddy. That is TAMAS. You are not renouncing the world — you are HIDING from it. And Krishna calls it out directly. Your PRESCRIBED duties — the responsibilities that come with your role in life — cannot be abandoned. Period."
