          translation: "One who gives up action because it is painful or out of fear of physical discomfort — such renunciation is rajasic, and one never obtains the fruit of true relinquishment.",
          modernInterpretation: "RAJASIC renunciation — the second type. This is the person who gives up their duty not because they are deluded like the tamasic type, but because the work is HARD, UNCOMFORTABLE, or PAINFUL. They calculate the cost-benefit and say, 'This is too much effort for too little reward. I am OUT.'\n\nThis is the gym member who cancels their membership because workouts are painful. The entrepreneur who abandons their startup because the first year was tough. The musician who stops practicing because their fingers hurt. They are not lazy in the tamasic sense — they are STRATEGIC quitters. They have done the math and decided the discomfort is not worth it.\n\nBut Krishna says something devastating: 'NAIVA TYAGA PHALAM LABHET' — they will NEVER get the true fruit of renunciation. Why? Because real growth ALWAYS involves discomfort. The butterfly MUST struggle out of the cocoon. The diamond MUST endure pressure. If you run away every time something gets hard, you are not renouncing — you are just COMFORT-SEEKING. And comfort-seeking dressed up as renunciation is just RAJASIC ego protecting itself. You feel smart for quitting, but you have actually gained NOTHING."
