          translation: "It is indeed impossible for an embodied being to abandon actions entirely. But one who renounces the fruits of action is called a true renouncer (tyagi).",
          modernInterpretation: "This is one of the most PRACTICALLY important verses in the entire Gita. Krishna states a simple biological FACT: as long as you have a BODY, you CANNOT stop acting. You breathe, you eat, you sleep, you think — these are ALL actions. Even a monk sitting in meditation is ACTING. Even deciding to do nothing is a DECISION, which is an action.\n\nSo the entire concept of 'I have given up all action' is a LOGICAL IMPOSSIBILITY. It is like saying 'I have decided to stop making decisions.' The statement contradicts itself. Krishna cuts through all the pretension and says: The REAL tyagi is not someone who stops acting. It is someone who stops being ATTACHED to the results of their actions.\n\nThis is incredibly LIBERATING. You do not have to quit your job to be spiritual. You do not have to move to the Himalayas. You do not have to give up your family. You just have to change your RELATIONSHIP with outcomes. Work hard, but do not be CRUSHED if you fail. Love deeply, but do not DEMAND that love be returned on your terms. Create art, but do not let critics determine your worth. THAT is true tyaga. And you can practice it RIGHT NOW, wherever you are, whatever you do."
