          transliteration: "jñānaṁ jñeyaṁ parijñātā tri-vidhā karma-codanā |\nkaraṇaṁ karma karteti tri-vidhaḥ karma-saṅgrahaḥ ||18||",
          words: [
            { word: "ज्ञानम्", transliteration: "jñānam", meaning: "knowledge" },
            { word: "ज्ञेयम्", transliteration: "jñeyam", meaning: "the object of knowledge" },
            { word: "परिज्ञाता", transliteration: "parijñātā", meaning: "the knower" },
            { word: "त्रिविधा", transliteration: "tri-vidhā", meaning: "threefold" },
            { word: "कर्मचोदना", transliteration: "karma-codanā", meaning: "the impetus/motivation for action" },
            { word: "करणम्", transliteration: "karaṇam", meaning: "the instrument" },
            { word: "कर्म", transliteration: "karma", meaning: "action" },
            { word: "कर्ता", transliteration: "kartā", meaning: "the doer" },
            { word: "इति", transliteration: "iti", meaning: "thus" },
            { word: "त्रिविधः", transliteration: "tri-vidhaḥ", meaning: "threefold" },
            { word: "कर्मसंग्रहः", transliteration: "karma-saṅgrahaḥ", meaning: "the basis/components of action" }
          ],
          translation: "Knowledge, the object of knowledge, and the knower — these three form the threefold impulse to action. The instrument, the action, and the doer — these three form the threefold basis of action.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna now gives us the ANATOMY of action — two interconnected trinities that explain WHY and HOW every action happens. First, the MOTIVATION trinity: Knowledge (what you know), the Object of Knowledge (what you are trying to know or achieve), and the Knower (you, the conscious agent). These three together CREATE the impulse to act.\n\nSecond, the EXECUTION trinity: the Instrument (the tools you use — body, senses, technology), the Action itself (the process), and the Doer (the agent performing it). These three together CARRY OUT the action.\n\nThink of it like cooking. The motivation side: you KNOW a recipe (knowledge), you want to make a specific dish (object), and YOU are the one who wants to cook (knower). The execution side: you use pots and pans (instrument), you follow the cooking process (action), and you are the chef (doer).\n\nKrishna is being a SYSTEMS THINKER here, breaking down action into its component parts. And He is doing this for a specific reason — in the next several verses, He will classify EACH of these components according to the three gunas. He is building a DIAGNOSTIC FRAMEWORK so you can look at any action in your life and understand EXACTLY what quality of consciousness is driving it."
