          translation: "Knowledge, action, and the doer are each declared to be of three kinds according to the distinction of the gunas, as described in Sankhya philosophy. Hear about them properly.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna is about to launch the MOST COMPREHENSIVE classification system in the Gita. Knowledge comes in three types. Action comes in three types. The doer comes in three types. And later — intellect, fortitude, and happiness will ALSO come in three types each. That is SIX categories, each with THREE variants = EIGHTEEN distinct classifications. In the EIGHTEENTH chapter. The symmetry is STUNNING.\n\nThis is Krishna being a PROFESSOR who is about to hand you the final exam study guide. He is saying: 'Everything I have taught you over 17 chapters about the three gunas? Here is the COMPLETE APPLICATION.' It is like a business school case study where you finally apply ALL the theories you learned.\n\nThe phrase YATHAVAT — 'as they truly are' — is key. Krishna is promising ACCURACY, not opinion. He is not sharing His personal preferences. He is describing REALITY as it IS. The gunas are not moral judgments — they are descriptions of NATURAL QUALITIES. Sattva is not 'good' in a moral sense — it is CLEAR. Rajas is not 'bad' — it is AGITATED. Tamas is not 'evil' — it is INERT. Understanding this distinction prevents you from turning spirituality into moralistic judgment."
