          translation: "That happiness which is deluding to the self both in the beginning and in the end, arising from sleep, laziness, and negligence — that is declared to be tamasic.",
          modernInterpretation: "TAMASIC happiness — and honestly, this might be the most RELEVANT to our modern epidemic of escapism. This happiness is MOHANAM — DELUDING — from beginning to end. It does not start as poison and become nectar (sattvic), nor does it start as nectar and become poison (rajasic). It is DELUSION all the way through. You THINK you are happy, but you are just NUMB.\n\nThe source? NIDRA (excessive sleep), ALASYA (laziness), and PRAMADA (negligence/carelessness). This is the happiness of the person who sleeps 14 hours, binge-watches TV all day, eats junk food on the couch, and says 'I am living my best life.' No, you are DYING slowly and calling it LIVING.\n\nThis is the Netflix-and-chill generation's warning verse. The happiness of avoidance. The comfort of not trying. The false peace of procrastination. You feel 'relaxed' because you are not engaging with any of life's challenges — but that relaxation is not peace, it is DECAY. A stagnant pond looks calm. A flowing river looks turbulent. But which one has LIFE in it?\n\nThe word MOHANAM hits hard — it DELUDES the SELF. You cannot even RECOGNIZE that this is not real happiness because the delusion is so complete. The person trapped in tamasic happiness genuinely believes they are content. Breaking out requires an external WAKE-UP CALL — a crisis, a truth-teller, or a deep moment of honest self-reflection."
