          translation: "The duties of brahmanas, kshatriyas, vaishyas, and shudras are distributed according to the qualities (gunas) born of their own nature, O Parantapa.",
          modernInterpretation: "This is one of the most DEBATED verses in the Gita, and it MUST be understood in context. Krishna says the duties of the four varnas are divided according to SVABHAVA-PRABHAVAIR GUNAIH — the gunas born of one's OWN NATURE. Not birth. Not family. Not surname. NATURE. Your inherent tendencies, your natural strengths, your dominant guna combination.\n\nThink of it like a modern personality assessment — not the Hogwarts kind, but the genuine psychological kind. Some people are naturally inclined toward KNOWLEDGE and TEACHING (brahmana temperament). Some toward LEADERSHIP and PROTECTION (kshatriya temperament). Some toward COMMERCE and AGRICULTURE (vaishya temperament). Some toward SERVICE and SKILL-WORK (shudra temperament). These are not hierarchies — they are FUNCTIONAL CATEGORIES based on natural aptitude.\n\nA doctor who loves teaching is expressing brahmana qualities. A CEO who leads and protects their company is expressing kshatriya qualities. An entrepreneur building a business is expressing vaishya qualities. A master craftsman or dedicated service professional is expressing shudra qualities. The same PERSON might express different varnas in different CONTEXTS. The key insight is SVABHAVA — your own nature. Do not force yourself into a role that contradicts your nature. Find what comes NATURALLY to you, and make that your offering to the world."
