          translation: "Agriculture, cattle-rearing, and trade are the natural duties of a vaishya, born of their own nature. Service is the natural duty of a shudra, born of their own nature.",
          modernInterpretation: "The vaishya and shudra profiles — BOTH described as SVABHAVAJAM, born of one's OWN NATURE. Vaishya duties center around PRODUCTION and COMMERCE: farming (creating food), animal husbandry (managing resources), and trade (distributing goods). In modern terms, this is the entrepreneur, the farmer, the businessperson, the financial advisor — anyone whose natural calling is to CREATE, GROW, and DISTRIBUTE wealth.\n\nShudra duty is PARICHARYA — SERVICE. And before anyone reads hierarchy into this, consider that SERVICE is the backbone of any civilization. The skilled craftsperson, the dedicated worker, the person whose excellence lies in DOING rather than theorizing or leading. In modern terms — the master chef, the brilliant software developer, the healthcare worker, the artisan, the essential worker who keeps society RUNNING.\n\nKrishna's ENTIRE point across verses 41-44 is not that some duties are SUPERIOR to others. The point is that different people have different NATURAL APTITUDES, and forcing yourself into a role that contradicts your nature creates suffering. The born teacher who becomes a businessman suffers. The born warrior who becomes a clerk suffers. The born entrepreneur who becomes a scholar suffers. SVABHAVA — know your nature, and work WITH it, not against it."
