          translation: "Each person, devoted to their own duty, attains perfection. Hear how one devoted to their own work finds perfection.",
          modernInterpretation: "This is the Gita's version of 'FOLLOW YOUR DHARMA.' SVE SVE KARMANI — in their OWN respective duty — a person attains SAMSIDDHI — PERFECTION. Not someone else's duty. Not the duty that society glorifies. Not the duty that pays the most. YOUR OWN duty.\n\nThis is Steve Jobs saying 'Your work is going to fill a large part of your life, and the only way to be truly satisfied is to do what you believe is great work.' This is Sachin Tendulkar who could have been anything, but was born to bat. This is A.R. Rahman who could have pursued any career, but was born to compose music. They found their SVA-KARMA and devoted themselves to it.\n\nThe word ABHIRATA is beautiful — it means DELIGHTED IN, DEVOTED TO, ENGAGED WITH JOY. It is not just doing your duty grudgingly. It is LOVING your duty. When you find the work that aligns with your nature, duty does not feel like a burden — it feels like PLAY. And through that joyful engagement, you reach SAMSIDDHI — complete perfection.\n\nKrishna is about to explain HOW this works in the next verse. The mechanism is stunning: you do not attain God by LEAVING your work. You attain God THROUGH your work. Your daily duty, done with devotion, IS your spiritual practice."
