          translation: "Better is one's own dharma, though imperfectly performed, than the dharma of another, well performed. One does not incur sin performing duty prescribed by one's own nature.",
          modernInterpretation: "Krishna REPEATS this verse from Chapter 3 (verse 35) — which means it is SO important He says it TWICE in the entire Gita. Better to do YOUR dharma BADLY than someone else's dharma PERFECTLY. Let that sink in.\n\nThe struggling musician who follows their passion is in a BETTER place spiritually than the person who becomes a brilliant banker despite their soul screaming for art. The average teacher who was BORN to teach is more fulfilled than the world-class corporate lawyer who wanted to be a teacher. Your dharma, even when it does not produce impressive results, creates NO karmic bondage. Someone else's dharma, even when executed brilliantly, creates inner CONFLICT.\n\nIn today's world of comparison culture — where everyone is benchmarking themselves against Instagram influencers and LinkedIn high-achievers — this verse is MEDICINE. Stop looking at what OTHERS are doing and doing it better than them. Start looking at what YOU were designed to do and doing it HONESTLY, even if imperfectly.\n\nThe word KILBISHAM — sin — is important. Krishna is not saying you will FAIL at your svadharma. He is saying even if you are IMPERFECT at it, you incur NO sin. Your nature protects you when you honor it. But when you violate your nature to chase someone else's dharma, no matter how successful you are externally, something inside you DIES. That inner death is the real sin."
