          translation: "One should not abandon one's inborn duty, O son of Kunti, even if it has faults. For all undertakings are enveloped by faults, as fire is covered by smoke.",
          modernInterpretation: "What a BEAUTIFUL and PRACTICAL analogy. Krishna says do NOT abandon your natural duty even if it has FAULTS — because ALL undertakings have faults, just as ALL fire comes with smoke. You cannot have fire without smoke. You cannot have action without imperfection.\n\nThis is the antidote to PERFECTIONISM. The person who says 'I will not start my business until I have the perfect plan' — you will NEVER start. The person who says 'I will not get married until I find the perfect partner' — you will NEVER marry. The person who says 'I will not publish until my writing is flawless' — you will NEVER publish. There IS no flawless action. There is no smoke-free fire.\n\nKrishna uses the word SAHAJAM — INBORN, NATURAL. Your natural duty may be messy, imperfect, full of challenges. But it is YOURS. A mother's love is sometimes imperfect — she makes mistakes, she overreacts, she worries too much. But should she STOP loving? A soldier's duty involves violence — an inherent 'defect.' Should they abandon national defense?\n\nThis verse gives PERMISSION to be imperfect. It says: Start. Do the work. Accept the smoke. The fire of your dharma WILL burn through, smoke and all. The only real failure is not lighting the fire at all because you were afraid of the smoke."
