          transliteration: "brahma-bhūtaḥ prasannātmā na śocati na kāṅkṣati |\nsamaḥ sarveṣu bhūteṣu mad-bhaktiṁ labhate parām ||54||",
          words: [
            { word: "ब्रह्मभूतः", transliteration: "brahma-bhūtaḥ", meaning: "one with Brahman" },
            { word: "प्रसन्नात्मा", transliteration: "prasannātmā", meaning: "serene-souled/joyful self" },
            { word: "न शोचति", transliteration: "na śocati", meaning: "does not grieve" },
            { word: "न काङ्क्षति", transliteration: "na kāṅkṣati", meaning: "does not desire" },
            { word: "समः", transliteration: "samaḥ", meaning: "equal/even-minded" },
            { word: "सर्वेषु", transliteration: "sarveṣu", meaning: "toward all" },
            { word: "भूतेषु", transliteration: "bhūteṣu", meaning: "beings" },
            { word: "मद्भक्तिम्", transliteration: "mad-bhaktim", meaning: "devotion to Me" },
            { word: "लभते", transliteration: "labhate", meaning: "attains" },
            { word: "पराम्", transliteration: "parām", meaning: "supreme" }
          ],
          translation: "Established in Brahman, serene-souled, one neither grieves nor desires. Equal toward all beings, such a person attains supreme devotion to Me.",
          modernInterpretation: "This verse is a MASTERPIECE of spiritual psychology. What does a person who has realized Brahman LOOK like in daily life? PRASANNATMA — serene, joyful soul (not grim-faced asceticism — genuine LIGHTNESS). NA SHOCHATI — does not grieve (losses do not crush them). NA KANKSHATI — does not crave (desires do not pull them). SAMAH SARVESHU BHUTESHU — equal toward ALL beings (no favorites, no enemies).\n\nBut the STUNNING conclusion is: MAD-BHAKTIM LABHATE PARAM — such a person attains SUPREME DEVOTION to Me. Wait — devotion AFTER Brahman-realization? Is not Brahman-realization the END? Krishna is saying NO. Brahman-realization is not the FINAL destination — it is the DOORWAY to the deepest love. When you dissolve your ego completely, what remains is not emptiness — it is PURE LOVE for the Divine.\n\nThis is Krishna brilliantly UNIFYING Jnana (knowledge) and Bhakti (devotion). The intellectual path leads to Brahman-realization. And Brahman-realization spontaneously flowers into SUPREME DEVOTION. Knowledge and love are not opposites — knowledge, taken to its ULTIMATE depth, BECOMES love. The scientist who studies the universe deeply enough eventually feels AWE. The philosopher who thinks deeply enough eventually feels WONDER. That awe, that wonder, that love — THAT is para bhakti."
