          modernInterpretation: "THE FINAL VERSE. The last word of the Bhagavad Gita. And it is a PROPHECY wrapped in a PROMISE.\n\nWhere Krishna is — the Divine, the Guru, the Supreme Consciousness — and where Arjuna is — the sincere seeker, the devoted student, the one who shows up despite confusion — THERE you will find FOUR things: ŚRĪ (prosperity), VIJAYA (victory), BHŪTI (glory), and DHRUVĀ NĪTI (certain righteousness).\n\nThis is not just about the Mahabharata war. This is about YOUR life. When YOU align with the Divine (your inner Krishna) and show up with sincerity (your inner Arjuna) — fortune finds you, victory follows you, glory surrounds you, and righteousness becomes unshakeable.\n\nSanjaya ends with 'MATIR MAMA' — this is MY conviction. The entire Gita began with Dhritarashtra's QUESTION. It ends with Sanjaya's CONVICTION. From doubt to certainty. From blindness to vision. From a question about war to an answer about LIFE.\n\nAnd so the Bhagavad Gita closes. Seven hundred verses. Eighteen chapters. One chariot. Two friends. And a conversation that changed the world FOREVER.\n\nHARE KRISHNA. JAI SHRI KRISHNA.\n\nOM TAT SAT — Thus ends the Srimad Bhagavad Gita, the Yoga Shastra, the Brahma Vidya, the dialogue between Sri Krishna and Arjuna. The Song of God is complete. But for the one who truly listens — it never ends. It BEGINS again. Every single day."
